   As some of you may have heard, I'm currently rewritting CalChart.  If 
you've never used CalChart before, go ahead and delete this.  But if you 
have any dislikes about the current version and want to offer 
suggestions, read on.  That said, here are some things that I'll 
definately implement:
   * Compatibility with our network (using C should take care of this)
   * Support Super VGA for better resolution and speed
   * Printing from within the program, including continuity (in Postscript, 
       based on the printing program I wrote last semester)
   * Animating a show from either alumni or student side.
   * Play automatically without clicking for every beat without 3-button 
       mouse.
   * Better editing of stuntsheets- deleting groups of stuntsheets, moving
       a stuntsheet, etc.
   * Renumbering stuntsheets that have identical points but different 
       labels.  Basically make the "hook" command easier.
   * Shows saved in a single file- save disk space as well.
   * Nice GUI interface
   * Easy portability to other platforms (not a big concern really, but a 
       good design helps and maybe someday someone will a Mac version?)

   And here are some other things I'll try to do:
   * Eliminate the use of animation files (I think this is probably 
       technically feasible, especially since we've moved the band's 
       computers up to 486's)
   * Improve the user interface, maybe select points and then change the 
       symbol, move them, etc. (moving single points will be the same) I 
       could really use suggestions here.
   * More commands, like GV, etc.

   Finally, some things already suggested that may not get done:
   * Play MIDI files along with the show (not feasible until the band 
       gets a sound card in the computers)
   * 3D view of the show (I don't think a 3D view of the dots will help- 
       you need real 3D objects to be useful.  Maybe export into a 3D
       rendering program?)
   * Desktop publishing features, such as drawing in the arrows, etc. 
       (Probably a little too ambitious, but who knows?)

   So if anyone has additional suggestions, e-mail them to me, or come 
talk to me.  At the moment, the program can load shows and print them, 
and the GUI is mostly done.  I'm beginning to draw the stuntsheets on the 
screen.  So it's not too late for suggestions.  When it gets to be 
somewhat useful, I'll put it in BRH so people can play with it if they want.

Gurk



From dci@math.uchicago.edu Tue Dec 13 12:35:18 1994
