> 
>    Okay, as far as the GUI, I have written too much of the specific 
> interface, but rather just the GUI library.  So I can build menus and 
> buttons and scroll bards, button to enter text and so on.  Right now, you 
> can load a file through a decent file requestor (you can scroll through 
> the list, change drives, etc).  You can then print them through a 
> requestor that let's you pick the file name of the postscript file, the 
> printing mode, and so on.
>    I'm writing the DOS version under a version of the GCC compiler and a 
> graphics library called GRX that supports SVGA, VGA, EGA, and Hercules 
> graphics.  There's a really low-level stub interface for quick porting 
> to other platforms.  Right now it also runs under UNIX/X because 
> development is much easier that way.  The inferface could be rewritten 
> with a little more work for a native GUI, so under X/Mac/Windows the 
> menus and buttons are normal system things.
>    Anyway, on the user-level it can run on different size screen and 
> even on B&W displays (for Mac, Hercules, X).

Nothing to comment on here really.  I'm not really a programmer, so I
don't know about all the "internal" stuff.  However, it sounds like these
underpinnings will make the program much more flexible.

>    As for renumbering, I didn't mean to change the letters to numbers or 
> whatever.  I meant that sometimes the charter screws up the middle of a 
> show or trys to change a flow in the middle and the formations are right 
> but the points are in the wrong place.  He then has to make a copy of the 
> show, delete the first half of one and the second half of another, and 
> then hook them.  I wanted to make this a little easier.

OK, I think you misunderstood me the other time.  In order to define a
renumbering of any sort (letter to number or whatever), a one-to-one
correspondence must be created between the old labels and the new labels. 
For example, A1 goes to T3, A2 goes to 144, A3 goes to YOUR_MOM, etc.

The question I am considering is how the user defines this correspondence.
One possible method: all the old labels are listed on the screen in
columns, and the user types in a new label next to each old label.  This
is perhaps the most obvious and primitive method, but it is a HUGE pain in
the ass for the user.

There is a much better method: the user creates two stuntsheets such that
the set of locations on each are identical.  Then the correspondence is
naturally defined by identity of location (this is the method used by the
current CalChart).

I think we both agree that a "graphical" method such as the second one is
preferable to a "text" method.  Now the question is to pin down the
details so that the whole process is internal and doesn't require file
manipulation and such.

Here is my suggestion.  In order to renumber, two stuntsheets must exist
back-to-back such that the set of locations is the same on each.  The only
difference can be in the labels.  Then the relabeling command will merge
these two sheets into one and will relabel all sheets that occur AFTER
these two OR will relabel all sheets that occur BEFORE these two (the
user's option for BEFORE or AFTER).

One important thing about this is that there has to be an error-checking
routine to make sure that the correspondence is well-defined.  It is
possible that two points could share the same location, in which case the
relabeling command should return an error message and NOT execute.

While we're on the subject of relabeling, what about processes for
changing the labels for an entire show (instead of merely reordering the
current ones)?  Allowing the set of labels to change in the midst of a
show will wreak havoc with the animation since destinations will not be
clear is the labels are different. 

I suggest making two routines for this situation.  The first is a "start
from scratch" routine; it calls the same routine that is used when first
creating a show.  The assignment of labels to points would be arbitrary,
just as it is when first creating a show.

The second is a "point by point" routine.  Select a point (or set of
points), and then type the new label.  The label will be changed on all
stuntsheets simultaneously.

If someone really wants to have a series of stuntsheets on which the
labels change, then different shows should be created for each set of labels.

Now what about changing the number of points?  For deleting points, just
type in the labels, and they're erased from all sheets.  As for adding
points, again type in the labels (check to be sure that the labels don't
already exist), and they appear in the southwest corner just off the grid.

How do these new features sound to you?  Can you think of any other useful
processes?

>    I have a little more to say about selecting points.  I definately want 
> to allow the user to be able to move a single point just by clicking on 
> it.  But group moves should be done differently.  Say that there's a 
> block that the user wants to flip along its center.  Genius move can do 
> this, but since the original and new positions overlap, it's a little 
> tricky.  Oh, and I do intend to implement a lasso.

Maybe geniusmove should be split into several commands that are more
intuitive.  The operations allowable by geniusmove are precisely the
"affine transformations" of the plane (Ax + b, where A = 2x2 matrix, x and
b are column vectors).  Mathematically speaking, any affine transformation
is the product of rotations, reflections, shears, and translations (a
shear is like a box becoming a parallelogram, where everybody marches NS
to position).  

Practically speaking, geniusmove is almost never used for anything but 
rotations, reflections, shears, and shears composed with a translation.
Of course, the last two are really the same since a shear = a shear
composed with the zero translation.

It might be a good idea to make separate commands for these three
actions.  Right now geniusmove is too abstract for most users.  However,
if more specific (but less powerful) commands were built, it would be much
easier for them.  As long as the ORIGINAL geniusmove is preserved also,
there is no loss of functionality.  This whole situation is analogous to
the relationship between FOUNTAIN and NSEW.

How would the user define such actions?  A reflection is determined by a
line, and a line is determined by two distinct points.  Hence a reflection
could be defined by the user selecting two points along that line. 

A rotation is determined by a center and an angle, so a rotation could be
defined by the user selecting the center of rotation, and then moving a
single point to determine the angle.

A shear composed with translation is a little harder to deal with.  Let me
think about this one for a while, and I'll get back to you on it.

All of these definitions should be "preserved" until overridden by a new
defintion.  This way, the user can apply the same action to several sets
of points in succession without having to redefine.  This is the way that
geniusmove (and blockmove) currently work.

Once you decide on a specific format, I'll be happy to do the mathematics
for you.

Speaking from the experience of spending hours and hours in the computer
room inputting data, I am firmly of the opinion that all types of moves
should be as easy and quick as possible, even if it means that other tasks
are harder.

Here's an idea that I'm not convinced is best, but it's worth
thinking about.  The user selects between two major modes - move mode and
"everything else" mode.  Move mode works similarly to move mode currently
does.  The action on selected points is implicitly defined.

In everything else mode, selecting a set of points doesn't cause any
action.  The user has to choose an action from the list of all possible
routines (INCLUDING movement).


>    I think that's about it for now.

Please let me know what you think about all of these ideas.  The best way
to come to the ideal solution is to bounce notions off someone else to see
what they think.
 
> P.S. I got denied from Stunt.  But at least this way I have no choice but 
> to concentrate on the two things that really matter to my future: 
> computers and school.  In case you're wondering, next year's Stunt is 
> Brad K., Mary, Neil, and Keisha.

The situation may be a little difficult for you politically, but you
should really try to work with Stunt and Erin on this project.  They might
have some good ideas, too.  Actually, to be perfectly honest, I have found
that fairly few people (stunt members included) have had good ideas for
the program, except for Martin Haye and myself.  The only exception that I
can think of right now is that Michelle Sintov suggested that we install
Kill.  Most people don't think of Calchart as a dynamic object - they
consider it a fixed tool, and they are forced to work under the conditions
imposed by it.  In my opinion, this mentality in conjunction with a
greater and greater dependence on Calchart has caused an increasing
"mathematization" of our charting.  This is not necessarily a bad thing,
just a change.

Dan


