> I think it would be easier to just implement the first method, then the 
> user can create a duplicate sheet and move the points around and then 
> have the program renumber everything.  Typing everything in seems a 
> little tedious.

Good.  We are in agreement on this, then.
 
> 
> Actually, for deleting points, you could just select the points, and then 
> pick "Remove Points From Show" or something similar.

Yes, of course you are right.  I hadn't thought about this carefully enough.
 
> 
> Yeah, I've taken Math 50B and CS 184 (graphics) so I know my shears.  But 
> you forgot scales (which a reflective is).  It's probably more intuitive 
> to say, reflection about this line, than to say, scale the X axis by -1.

Well, there are several ways to generate the set of affine
transformations.  I don't remember offhand which "special" transformations
generate which others.  When the actual implementation occurs, I'll do the
rigorous mathematics.  You are definitely right in the sense that
dilations should be added to the list of special commands.  A dilation is
a diagonalizable transformation with no negative eigenvalues, while a
scale is an arbitrary diagonalizable transformation.

For example, a dilation would apply when a twostep block becomes a
fourstep block.

All 2dimensional scales are either dilations; dilations
composed with a reflection; or dilations composed with a 180deg rotation.

Something else that occurred to me last night.  Block move is also just a
special case of geniusmove, albeit very very useful.  So, the working list
of "special transformations" is now: reflection, rotation, shear,
dilation, and translation.

Note that further restrictions should probably be made for these cases. 
For example, reflection lines should only be N-S, E-W, NW-SE, or NE-SW. 
And the same requirement should be placed on the "invariant" lines of shears.

> 
> Yes, I've noticed many people doing things by hand that could be done 
> with genius move.

This is the number one reason that I always said to stunt, "I can do
anything in half the time it would take you."  And it was generally true.

> 
> How about buttons for the different modes?  There could be a rectangular 
> selection button, a lasso button, a move mode button, etc.  In the 
> selection modes, you select a group of points and then choose an action.
> 

I like the sound of this.  By "button," I assume you mean an icon on the
screen.  Click the icon and get that mode.  Maybe lasso and rectangular
modes should not be separate.  How about right and left mouse buttons?

> 
> Sounds good, but designing the specifics will be a little more 
> complicated.  One thing I'm still debating is if selecting points first 
> and then doing various actions can be as fast as the current method.  
> Moving indivual points can be handled the same, and moving blocks and 
> genius move are basically the same, but smart move doesn't seem to fit in 
> very well.

Smartmove was always a special case, even in the earliest versions of the
program.

OK.  Here is a complete idea for move mode.  My mental picture looks
something like those Macintosh drawing programs with icons on the left
side of the screen.  I'm not sure if this will fit in with the other
elements of your GUI, so let me know.  Click with the left button to move
a single point.  Click with the right button to smartmove.  Drag with the
left button for rectangular selection.  Drag with the right button for
lasso selection.  After selection, click (with either button) on one of a
series of icons along the edge of the screen: rotation, translation,
geniusmove, etc. 

But this presents the problem of how to define the "special" actions, like
reflection.  How does communicate the fact that the next two clicks will
represent points on the reflection line?  Perhaps click on the DEFINITION
icon, and then click on reflection.  Then the definition of the reflection
would remain intact until the next definition of reflection.  Hmm.  This
seems rather cumbersome.

For "everything else" mode, the set of icons would change to a different set:
label, continuity, etc.

What about reference points?  This provides a special display problem. 

> It took me a while to realize, but it's actually good that I'm not DM or 
