> 
> Hmmm.  I hadn't heard that term.  Of course, saying something like 
> "Resize block" would probably be the most intuitive.

I guess this term would apply, but I'm not so sure that it is very
descriptive for dilating along a diagonal.  Perhaps "adjust spacing."
 
> > 
> > Note that further restrictions should probably be made for these cases. 
> > For example, reflection lines should only be N-S, E-W, NW-SE, or NE-SW. 
> > And the same requirement should be placed on the "invariant" lines of shears.
> 
> Except, this is really a subset of the actions you can do with genuis 
> move.  What if you have a 4 step block that you want to reflect or shear 
> along NNW-SSE for instance?

Yes, but the original geniusmove will be able to do these other things.  I
think the best system would be to figure out exactly what is MOST commonly
used and make special commands out of just those few things.  All other
things could always be accomplished with the old command.  

How many times have you ever had to reflect about a NNW-SSE line?  Sure,
it's nice to know that it's possible, but I wouldn't worry about making it
particularly efficient.

This philosophy is the same as my reasons for not wanting a "show high
NSEW" command.  Instead, FOUNTAIN should just be changed to allow for a
stepsize.  "high step NSEW" is so useful that it should have a special
command, but "show high NSEW" is fairly uncommon.
 
> > I like the sound of this.  By "button," I assume you mean an icon on the
> > screen.  Click the icon and get that mode.  Maybe lasso and rectangular
> > modes should not be separate.  How about right and left mouse buttons?
> 
> Sure.  I'm not ruling out a Mac version in the future, but I guess the 
> right button can be emulated with the keyboard.

It seems to me that having to switch between rectangular blocking
and lassoing would be a huge pain in the ass.  I can well imagine using
both in close alternation.

This reminds me to suggest that you preserve the "interactive" aspect to
blocking.  That is, the currently selected points should be highlighted as
they are selected.  This makes it SO much easier to tell whether you've
really selected the correct region.  This works so well because our whole
situation is "discrete" (i.e., every object consists of points, not lines
or regions).
 
> 
> Well, maybe we can do without the defination thing.  Just have a message 
> that says "Drag out a reflection line or press ESC".  Or maybe this is 
> better: for reflections, just have "Flip X" and "Flip Y" options.  For 
> the other transformations, have certain presets like "Rotate CCW 90 degs" 
> and also allow variable transformations by showing a wireframe box that can 
> be rotated, sheared, etc.  Any reflection can be composed of X and Y 
> reflections and rotations, right?  (Just off the top of my head, it seems 
> to work).  Maybe something along these lines?  Of course, moving might be 
> a little weird.  Maybe show the selected points move around like a brush 
> in a paint program.

I like the idea of ESC.  If you want the already defined action,
just press one key.  Otherwise, make the definition.

In fact, any reflection can be made by composing rotations with just one
fixed reflection.  But that's not really the point.  We don't want
to force people to do weird combinations of moves when all they want to do
is turn one simple triangle around.  If things aren't going to be very
simple, then they might as well be the old way.

In my opinion, we could completely deal with all reflections with four icons:
flip NS, flip EW, flip NW-SE, flip NE-SW.  After choosing one, you would
just have to click on any point along the reflection line (or hit ESC). 
I'll use the term "cardinal" from now on to refer to one of these four
directions.

As for shears, dilations, and rotations, I'd make the same kind of
restriction.  Require that the fixed line of the shear be a cardinal line,
and require that the direction of the dilation be along a cardinal (i.e.,
one of the eigenvalues = 1, the other is positive, and the eigenvector of
the latter eigenvalue is cardinal).  In order to dilate in more than one
direction (e.g., 4x4 block to 2x2 block), two dilations would have to be
used.  However, I think that this composition is intuitive enough even for
stunt members to understand. 

To define a dilation, the user would have to click a point on the fixed
line (perpendicular to the direction of dilation) and then move a single
point.  To define a shear, click on the fixed line and move a single
point.  In both these cases, the movement of the point would be restricted
along a line determined by the already-established fixed line.  To define
a rotation, click on the center.

Unfortunately, this makes for a lot of icons: 4 + 4 + 4 + 7 (7 nonidentity
rotations).  Alternately, we could reduce each type of action to a single
icon, and then when the user dragged a direction, the program would "round
off" to the nearest cardinal.

> Actually you could just select the points and then pick "Set symbol" or 
> whatever either from a menu or from an icon.

I like the idea of allowing for more than one way to do something.  Then
hardware specifics are less likely to cause trouble (e.g., only a 1-button
mouse).  I would suggest icons, pulldown-menus, AND keyboard commands.  I
have found that mouse-driven menus (icons and pulldowns) are easier to
learn, but keyboard commands are much faster for experienced users.
 
> 
> Somethings would be different at the programmier's level, but from the 
> user's perspective it should all be the same.  Maybe just have icons to 
> select which reference points to edit.

I don't see any reason to limit the number of reference points.  Might as
well have as many as desired by the user.
 
> I don't think it would be too hard.  I did all this stuff in my graphics 
> class last semester.  But 3-D people would add a lot more work.  A 3-D 
> view of a plane would be pretty easy.

What about rectangular boxes: 55 inches high, 25 inches wide, and 15
inches deep.  Perhaps some simple coloring, too, like white for the upper
half of the front and gold for the upper half of the back.
 
> 
> Actually it's nice that you are interested.  You seem to be the only one 
> I can really bounce ideas of off.

I'm sorry if my terminology (icons, pulldown menus, etc.) is somewhat
inaccurate.  As I mentioned, I'm not really a programmer, so I don't
know about lots of things that you probably consider elementary.  I hope
my language doesn't make me sound too clueless.

I realized that I used the pronoun "we" several times in this letter.  If
I weren't too lazy, I'd go back and change them to "you" out of respect
for the fact that all I'm doing is answering a few stupid emails.

Dan


