> 
>    One of the few good suggestions from someone other than you was an 
> idea that Chris Hack gave me.  He suggestioned a "random continuity 
> error" feature to simulate an actual performance, with the degree selectable 
> of course.  This sounds a little ludicrous at first, but if you think 
> about it, it could be pretty useful, not just to simulate blatant 
> continuity mistakes, but also to simulate bad alignment, step size, etc.  
> If I decide to try to create a fairly realistic view of the show, this 
> could add in very well.

I don't know about this.  First of all, blatant continuity mistakes are
impossible to simulate accurately by their very nature.  Simulations of
infrequent but large events is not statistically meaningful.  It is much
more plausible to simulate a continuous low-level error such as bad
alignment.  However, this feature won't be useful unless you get 3D
rendering first.  So I'd put it off until after you get that part working.
I'm starting to have some ideas on the mathematical representation of bad
alignment.  After I think about it some more, I'll let you know about it.

>    Okay, maybe this is more than one thing, but I received some confusing 
> comments from Stunt.  This is kind of a generalization of their views, 
> but they seem think that a 3-D planar view of the show will help them 
> visualize problems of flows on the computer translating to the real 
> thing.  I think that the perspective has very little to do with this, but 
> rather, it's having 3-D people instead of points and not having perfect 
> alignment.  These two things make flows much "muddier".  In fact, I'm now 
> almost convinced that a planar 3-D view would be pointless.  So, I'll 
> probably have a 3-D rendering program do all the work, or if I have extra 
> time to kill, I could digitize people marching and paste these animations 
> in place of the dots.  Some people seemed concerned that a 3-D view would 
> make charting rely on the computer too much, but I think that's already 
> happening and this could at least help charters visulize what it will 
> really look like.

I entirely agree that the planar view won't help.  The planar view would
only help for designing things like words or phantom masks, but that's
already fairly easy.

Your ideas are very appropriate.  What makes a block look like a block?
It's not the bandsmen; it's the empty space BETWEEN the bandsmen.  Without
the space in between, the formation consists of nothing more than its border.

The problem is that at twostep spacing, distance between bandsmen is less
than the width of the bandsmen.  Hence, the empty space is bound to be
obscured.  You may have noticed that fourstep blocks almost always look
better than twostep blocks.  However, twostep blocks make the band sound
better.

I'd have to oppose digitization of bandsmen because this would be too
technology dependent - so much memory and processor speed required.  It's
best to have things work on a wide variety of equipment.  I guess it would
be OK if there was also a "primitive rectangle" option.

There is some historical perspective that might be useful in considering
the philosophic value of 3d viewing.  I don't have time to type it right
now since I have to go home to watch the simpsons in 30 minutes.  But I'll
write all about it tomorrow.

Dan


