> 
> Sorry, I didn't realize you could dilate along a diagonal.

Orientation is unimportant.  A transformation is called diagonalizable if
it can be diagonalized with respect to SOME basis.  That is, it has two
independent eigenvectors.  These eigenvectors can be in any direction, and
they don't have to be perpendicular, but of course they can't be parallel.
 
> 
> I considering replacing genius move with these basic transformations.  
> But I guess the power user would find that a pain, and doing the basic 
> things would take a little longer.

You should definitely keep the old geniusmove around.  I have definitely
been in situations where none of our new proposed actions would work well.
The problem is that compositions of planar transformations is not always
such an obvious thing.  Even someone with a lot of mathematical
background, like you or me, can have a lot of trouble trying to figure out
how to decompose a given transformation into rotations and shears and
things.  And it would certainly be out of the question for a typical
clueless stunt member.

>From my perspective, the whole reason that your project is necessary is
that Martin and I were not wise enough to make things even more flexible
than we thought would be necessary (see history).  I don't want to make
the same mistake twice.
 
> 
> If the system only has one mouse button, you could either hold down a 
> key, say the shift key, and press the mouse button, or separate rectangle 
> and lasso button could appear.  The first way would definately be easier 
> and less system dependant, but the second way might be a little more 
> intuitive on Macs.

This isn't that important to me.  Either way sounds fine.  I'd go with
whatever seems easier to you.  Actually, I think the shift key method is
better since it's conceivable that someone would try to operate a PC with
a one-button mouse.
 
> 
> Actually, I meant to use the ESC key to abort the transformation, but I 
> like this idea.

And I like the idea of aborting.  ESC should be reserved for aborting in
all contexts, so maybe RETURN for repeat the previous action.  Come to
think of it, this idea could be widened.  If you select some points and
then immediately hit RETURN without selecting an action, then the previous
action is repeated, whatever it is.  If the last command was a flip, then
RETURN will cause a flip.  I'm sure you get the idea.  Of course, there
could also be a "repeat" icon, which could be used as described above, or
it could be used AFTER choosing reflection to mean "apply the most recent
reflection, even if it was not the most recent action."  If this does not
make sense, I'll explain it again.

I suppose that there might be some actions which are inherently
"non-repeatable," such as undo. If you undo an action, you can't select a
group of points and apply the same undo to that group.  In this case,
"repeat-the-last-action" would return an error.  It's probably NOT wise to
simply repeat the most recent repeatable action, since you could end up
accidentally doing something from half an hour ago. 
 
> 
> Yes, make it as simple as possible.  If there are too many icons, menus 
> can be used.  For a reflection for instance, you click on the reflection 
> icon, a menu pops up, and then you click on the type of reflection.

ah, submenu is the way to go.  One icon for each of the types, then a menu
to choose the direction, and finally mark points (like center of rotation).
 
> 
> Well, there might not be much room for more icons, but keyboard shortcuts 
> are a definate plus.

I would suggest that EVERY single feature be executable by menu and by
keyboard.  Also, the commonly used features should appear as
icons.

I think that our idea of "move mode" and "everything-else mode" fits in
with this plan in the following way.  The set of icons does not have to be
fixed.  In move mode, the icons are all of the geniusmove derivatives and
stuff like that.  In the other mode, the icons represent stuff like
continuity select, flip label, etc.
 
> 
> Well, I didn't think the limit of 3 was much of a problem.  If the number 
> is flexible, how do you deal with deleting a reference point group?  So 
> you hit zap or something, but then it has to go through the continuity 
> and change all R2 references to R1.  If you just leave R1 empty, things 
> could get messy.  Maybe naming the reference sheets?

I agree that it's not much of a problem, and sometimes losers are too
dependent on reference points.  They use them in ugly ways to make their
continuity work when there are much simpler and more beautiful ways of
doing it.  However, once or twice I have had a need for 4 reference
points.  In these cases, I've ended up adding extra sheets that were never
printed or distributed.

Ok, I guess there has to be SOME limit because the parser has to be able
to handle the names.  How about 10, which are referenced by the codes R0 - R9?
This seems logical.  Don't deal with deleting reference groups at all. 
Just preserve the current mechanism.  To save memory, don't bother
recording locations if all of the reference points are identical with the
original points.

With this potential problem of file size and the problem with ugly
continuity described above, I would suggest intentionally somewhat
obscuring the fact that there are so many possible reference points by
making it not obvious how to access them unless you know how.  I'm not
sure what this means exactly.  But what I DON'T want is ten icons across
the top of the screen labeled R0 through R9.
 
> 
> Sure.  If I implement the 3-D inside the program, I will be somewhat 
> platform dependant no matter what (if it has to go fast).  If I use an 
> external program, it's more of a proofing feature because it will be so 
> slow.  But the external program could use the digitized bandsmen, which 
> wouldn't be platform dependant (if this program is available on all 
> machines, but something public domain like POVRay would be).

See, the problem is that stunt doesn't want a proofing feature.  They want
an exploratory tool.  They want to be able to try out an idea as soon as
they get it to see if it really works as well as their incredibly creative
minds think it will.  So, anything slow is going to end up not being used,
or being used with a huge pain in the ass.

I didn't really mean platform dependent, I meant hardware dependent. 
Slower chips and weaker graphics cards are going to have a major negative
impact on the usefulness of a display with digitized bandsmen.
 
> I understand what you're saying.

I'm doing my best to emulate your language, so I hope you know what you
are talking about.  Otherwise, I'm learning bad habits.
 
> 
> Maybe, but your suggestions are altering the way I was going to do this, 
> so I don't take offence.

Good, I'm glad to be able to stick my nose where it doesn't belong
anymore.  Keep up the good work - you're well on your way to making it
into the second volume of the history book (see p.85).
 
> About spring show, I don't do it yet, but it will only take a weekend or 
> so.  I talked to Erin about the dimensions of the stage and see said that 
> they're waiting for Rune to get them.  That was a while ago, though, so 
> maybe I should go bug someone.  I've looked at the old shuntsheets, but I 
> wasn't really thinking about printing the stage on there.  I think the 
> dimensions should be configurable.  Who knows, we might not always be in 
> Zellerbach.  But maybe I can load a postscript file from a drawing 
> program and superimpose it on top.  Or maybe they can just change the 
> code in the future.  However, for all the spring shows in Zellerbach so 
> far, we've had the Harmon decorations on the stuntsheets.  Oh, I was 
> wondering why the 'A' line is 4 steps off the sideline on the old spring 
> show stuntsheets.  No one here seems to know.

I think you should just write it to work with Zellerbach.  It's impossible
to try to deal with all possible stage shapes simultaneously.  If it's not
too hard, I would continue to allow to print Harmon sheets just in case we
ever go back.  How often are we going to move?  Once every 30 years? 
Fine, if the bands needs us in 30 years, I pledge to come back and help
rewrite the code for a new stage.

Actually, what we did for the last two years was print out the shows onto
Harmon stuntsheets.  Somewhere, we got a photocopy of a diagram of the
zellerbach stage.  We enlarged it to the proper size, and then we cut a
hole of the proper size and shape inside the diagram.  One by one, we took
the Harmon stuntsheets, covered them with the diagram-and-hole, and
photocopied.  These produced rather unprofessional but still functional
sheets.

I still think that you should print out some features to reflect the
geometry of zellerbach.  It might even help stunt avoid the nearly
insurmountable temptation to design flows requiring people to march
through thin air or into walls.
 
> Okay, so how about this interface: you can click on a single point and 
> move it, click on it with the right button for smart move, or you can 
> select points by dragging.  Left button is rectangular and right is 
> lasso.  Then you can select different menu options like symbol, 
> continuity, etc, or you can click different buttons for various 
> transformations.  Then you move a point or something depending on the 
> transformation (or you can hit a key to repeat the last one).  You can 
> also click on the genuis move icon and then move three points.  Any 
> suggestions?

Geniusmove should be based upon the last three single point moves, not on
the next three moves.  This is because sometimes you actually only need to
move two points to get the g-move you want.  In particular, this occurs
when you want a line to go to another line.  It doesn't matter what
happenned to the third point - the effect on the desired line will be the
same.  So, if I've been moving points around, then I want to g-move a
line, I only need to bother setting two points.

By the way, when you implement geniusmove, don't just copy the old code. 
Read my paper and use the formulae there.  The implemented version of
geniusmove is slightly stupider about checking for degenerate cases.

OK.  Here is an example to think about.  Task: move an 8man NW-SE diagonal
line at 2DM spacing, with the SE-most man on the hash at the 50; to an
8man E-W line at 2HS spacing, with the SE-most man becoming the E-most man
at the hash on the south 40.

1) Move each point individually.  Typical solution for an inexperienced
stunt member.

2) Move two points, then smartmove the rest.  Typical solution for an
experienced stunt member.

3) Select shear, choose N-S direction, and move a single point.  Typical
solution for you, me, or Martin Haye.

Here's the problem.  Someone who thinks he is a hot-shot (I won't name
names) is going to come along and try to be clever in doing this task.  He
looks at the first formation and looks at the second formation.  What does
it look like to him?  Rotate 45deg ccw, then translate.

So, he selects rotate, chooses the proper angle, and clicks on the SE-most
man as the center of rotation.  Uh oh.  There's a problem here.  The
spacing is too big.  That's strange - 2step spacing initially and 2step
spacing in the end.  Must be a bug in the program - have to tell Gurk
about it.

That's Ok.  Fix it by changing the block spacing.  Choose dilation, select
correct direction, and set a point.  NOW what's the matter?  The spacing
looks approximately correct, but it seems that some of the points are a
1/2step out of position!  Son of a bitch.

So, at this point he gives up and tries solution #1.

Do you see the problem here?  The first mistake is obvious - DM does not
equal HS.  But the second mistake is slightly more subtle.  sqrt(2) is
irrational, but the grid is rational.  So the locations of the points gets
rounded off after the first rotation.  This causes small errors later.


I see this as a fairly major problem.  How are we going to teach people to
decompose their transformations properly?  With the old g-move there is
no problem because there is no need for decomposition.

If you think I'm exaggerating in the above example, then you haven't been
around stunt much.

Dan


From dci@math.uchicago.edu  Ukn Jan 25 17:50:31 1995
