> 
> Maybe you can just cycle through the reference groups, create a new one,
> or zap one, and there's a label to show you which one you're editing.

This is not a terribly critical issue because reference points are not
used terribly often.  I've always felt that they were always a bit
inherently "ugly" as an abstract concept.  So I'm not terribly concerned
by implementing them in a nice manner.
 
> 
> That's true.  I think they only thing I can do that will be useful and
> also be used is to do a real 3-D view inside the program.  Of course, you
> don't need things like shading, so I might not be as much work as I was
> thinking (definately low priority at the moment, however).

OK, I'd say that you should put it at the bottom of the list.  Get
everything else working smoothly, then worry about 3D (if you haven't
graduated by then).
 
> 
> Do you know anything about the 'A'?  You seem to have skipped over this.

Oops, you're right.  I forgot to mention the A line.  I think I know the
reason why it was where it was, but I've never verified this by talking to
an older drum major.  I'll get in touch with Jones to see if he knows.

The floor of Harmon Gym is somewhat wider than 20 yards (distance from A
to E).  So there is some room around the edges of the grid, especially in
the back.  These spaces were used occasionally during marching segment,
especially in the back and on the sides.  Up in the front, the first row
of bleachers was basically right where "4-off-the-A" would be.  So there
was a little bit of room in the front (about two steps), but not a lot. 
In fact, bob's box was placed just off the Aline, as it is now.  So, he
was actually standing on the grid as shown on the harmon sheets.

So that's the reason.  The a line couldn't really be any closer to the
bleachers.  But it WAS physically feasible to place bandsmen west of the
Aline.  So the grid was expanded by 4 steps to accommodate this
possibility.

However, this extra space was not used very often.  It's really a bit too
close to the audience, and it's pretty tough to see bob way down there. 
It was primarily used at times when the flow just wouldn't work without one
more person at the end of the line.
 
> 
> Maybe the best thing is to just import a postscript file.  Then I can make
> it as pretty as I like.  The config file can piece everything together.  I
> think this might be easier than to write the code to draw it, and
> definately easier to fiddle with.

Whatever.  I can't think of any reason why importing is bad.  It would
only make a new stage easier to deal with.  However, I'd be careful in
thinking that being able to set the size of the grid will be helpful.  The
problem is that there are just too many possibilities, with locations of A
lines, non-rectangular shapes, and things like that.  I can't imagine how
all possibilities can be dealt with internally.  Most likely, some changes
are going to have to occur in the code itself.
 
> 
> Yeah, I suppose it looks cooler too.

See history to understand why I place a high value on cool-looking
stuntsheets, not just strictly informative sheets.
 
> 
> Right.  Something I think would help with a lot of this is to see your
> transformation.  So for genius move, you move three points, and there are
> lines drawn from the old locations to the new locations.  Then you
> press return and they're transformed.  Even if the user isn't very
> mathematical this could make sense.  So modify the above interface a
> little.  Select points with the left or right mouse button.  If you drag a
> selected point, a line appears showing the translation, and when you let
> go, they're moved.  If you click with the right button, the center of
> transformation is set (but how do you tell between lasso and a center that
> isn't set on a point?) and the currently selected transformation mode is
> actived.  You drag a point (with an appropriate line representation appearing)
> and the points are transformed.  You can also redo the last transformation.

I'm not sure if I understand this.  Let me try to explain it back to you. 
At any given moment, a certain transformation type is currently "active"
(translation, shear, rotation, geniusmove, etc.).  If NO points are
currently selected, then leftclicking on a point will move it. 
Rightclicking will smartmove it.  leftdragging will rectangularblock
select points.  rightdragging will lasso select points.

If SOME points are currently selected, then the program is expecting a
transformation definition.  Special key for repeating the last action. 
Special key for unselecting all points and returning to above situation
(abort).  To set fixed points, leftclick on a location (it may be an
actual man, it may not).  To move a point, leftdrag it.  Again, it may or
may not be an actual man.  These motions show up as lines, and the fixed
points show up as dots.  As soon as enough information is given to
uniquely determine an action on the set of selected points, the action
will execute. 

Come to think of it, this isn't exactly what you said.  But I like this idea.
The really neat thing is that different combinations of information can
uniquely determine the action.  For example, any combination of three
fixed points and motions will give a geniusmove.  The program doesn't care
which combination is actually used.  Shears can be determined by a fixed
point and a motion, or by two parallel motions.

Even more interestingly, the shape of the selected set can affect the
amount of necessary information.  In particular, suppose that all of the
selected points lie on a line.  Then it is possible for a geniusmove to be
determined by only two motions.  Or, consider shearing a line in the same
direction as that line (so it's actually just a translation).  This can
require only one piece of information if that one piece is properly chosen.

All of this stuff is mathematically calculatable using determinants and
stuff like that.  If we decide with this interface, I can't wait to draw
up the formulae.

One thing that we should think about is the idea of "editing" the set of
selected points.  What if you accidentally miss one?  There should be a
way to add it to the current set without having to start over.  Notice
that my scheme does not assign any special meaning to the right button
when SOME points are selected.  Perhaps lasso could be used to add or
subtract points.  That is, lassoing selected points will deselect, and
lassoing unselected points will select (this is a NOT operation).

Also, in the old version, points are automatically deselected after an
action.  Maybe this should no longer be the case.  No, come to think of
it, I think that the points should automaticlly be deselected because it
is generally unlikely to be using the same set of points in succession. 
It's more likely that the user will shift to another set.  However, define
a keystroke to "recall last selected set" if desired.

> Also, how useful are rotations?  Maybe 90 degree rotations, but most flows
> are on a 2 step grid.  Maybe other rotations should be left to genuis
> move?  One more thing.  There's got to be a better to do off-the-grid
> formations.  Granted, we rarely do them, but once I wanted to do a circle
> and it looked so bad, even after cutting out a piece of paper as a
> template, that I wrote a simple program to modify the stuntsheet.  Of
> course, this could easily be added latter.  Actually, it resembles the smart
> move in a way (a series of arbitrary points in a formation rather than a
> line).  I haven't thought about this much, but maybe the points could be
> defined as some sort of "mesh" and moving one point would affect others
> nearby.  Maybe there are more important things right now, but I'd like to
> do as much planning ahead as I can.

Whenever I had to make circles, I used to get out the hand calculator and
calculated trigonmetrically the locations of the points evenly spaced
around the circle.  Then I rounded off to the nearest halfstep.  A pain in
the ass, but the circles looked good (by definition, as good as possible).

You are absolutely right about 45degree rotations not being necessary.  As
seen in my example of last time, they are only useful for off-the-grid
formations.  So, we'll leave 45deg rotations to old g-move.  This reduces
the number of rotations to three.

Also, if we use the interface described by me above, we only need one
shear icon, not four.  Even if you know the direction of the shear, you
still have to move a point to define it.  But this motion itself gives the
direction of the shear, so there's no point in pre-specifying direction.
Same thing goes for dilations.

As for rotations and reflections, it still seems like a good idea to have
separate icons for each kind of action.  Then these actions would be
defined by a single fixed point (or by a single motion).

I definitely feel like things are clicking into place.  This interface is
going to be BY FAR better than anything either you or me could have
designed by ourselves.  I tell you, there's nothing quite so useful as
partner to bounce ideas off of.

Dan


