The subject of the shape of the Zellerbach grid has come up in several
contexts recently: writing the field setup manual, and also redesigning
CalChart.

Anyway, I've pieced together all the different aspects and have come to an
opinion as to the best solution to the problem.  It is:

Set the A line to be as close to the audience as possible so that the
ENTIRE line actually exists.  That is, it should just barely clear the
gaps on the sides of the pit.  Then, there will be enough room for the
B,C, and D lines.  Past the D line, there will be something around 4 or 6
steps to the back curtain (somebody should go to Zellerbach to measure
this so that stunt can chart properly).  Also, in front of the A line,
there will be about 2 steps for most (but not all) of the distance between
the 40yard lines (again, someone should take measurements to figure out
exactly how much room there really is).

To accommodate this space in front of the A line, the stuntsheets should
be changed slightly so that the grid starts 4 steps in front of the A line
(see the old Harmon sheets if you don't understand my description).

These are my reasons for this opinion.  First, it will be much easier for
field setup to tape the stage accurately if they don't have to worry about
dealing with gaps in the A line.  Much more importantly, it will be easier
for bandsmen to march if they don't have to deal with gaps in the A line.

As for rehearsals, it will be very easy for field setup to extend the
yardlines a few additional steps to the west.

There you go.

Dan


From dci@math.uchicago.edu Fri Jan 27 16:33:48 1995
