Here is something that we need to clarify.  What happens if you reselect
immediately after selecting men?  I suggested a NOT feature, so that the
set of points could easily be amended.  You suggested that reselecting
would immediately erase the old selection.  The problem here is that both
ideas have advantages, but of course only one can actually be implemented.
One or the other will have to be implemented by keystroke.

It seems to me that usually when I make a mistake in blocking, it is
because I missed a few points on the end, or I caught a few extras. 
Generally, it would be very easy to amend if the old version had such a
feature.

Sometimes I would make a mistake like: "oops, I wanted the south half of
the block, not the north half of the block."  In this kind of situation,
your idea would be more helpful.

However, without doubt the first kind of mistake occurs much more often. 
Therefore, I propose we go with the NOT feature.

More ideas, but I've got to run right now.

Dan



From dci@math.uchicago.edu Mon Jan 30 16:36:29 1995
