Status: RO
X-Status: 

> 
> I was sort of off on a tangent on the block move thing.  I was just 
> saying that it would exit this special transformation mode and then carry 
> out the left button action (translation).  This is not a good thing, I 
> was just wondering if that was what you were saying.

I'm still not clear on what you are saying.  How is the left button action
= translation?  Do you mean individualmove?  If so, it is best to think of
the translation action and individualmove as separate things.  In fact, it
seems to me that individualmove is actually the unique exception in our
overall consistent structure of actions.  I'm not disapproving, I'm just
clarifying the status of individualmove.
 
> I was thinking that if you click on an existing endpoint, you move it.  
> Otherwise, you create a new piece of information.  I guess this is 
> similar to moving reference points.  Right clicks could clear endpoints.  
> The drawback is that if the endpoint is on top of the start point of the 
> next input, you have to do things in a certain order.  But offhand, I 
> don't see this as much of a problem.

In my opinion, I think that endpoints on top of start points will be a
problem.  If we're trying to make it easy to input and change the data,
then why force the user to input in a certain order?  Here's a compromise.
Right click either endpoint to kill.  Left click to input new data.  Left
drag an existing endpoint to edit.

But what happens if two lines share the same endpoint?  How does the
program know which one to edit or kill?  Imagine the worst case, where two
lines are inverses of each other (same line, but source and destination
reversed).  In this case, there is literally no way to distinguish between
the two with the mouse.  A keyboard or menu solution will have to be
implemented.
 
> Okay, just to have these transformations clear, here is a list and the extra 
> information needed.
> 
> translation - 1 MAN movement
> genuis - 2 or 3 POINT movements
> rotation (180 deg or 90 deg CW/CCW: different menu items) - none
> shear - 1 POINT click and 1 POINT movement, or 2 parallel POINT movements
> reflection (N/S, E/W, NW/SE, NE/SW: different menu items) - 1 POINT click
> dilation - (not sure about the best way, 1 POINT click and 1 POINT movement?)

A rotation requires one point: the center of rotation.  Shears and
dilations can be defined by one movement if the movement is chosen wisely. 
As in shear, the way to define a dilation is by 1 click and 1 movement or
by 2 parallel movements.  Reflections can be defined by one movement (the
reflection line will be the perpendicular bisector).

With the exception of rotation, everything should be thought of as a
movement.  If you want a fixed point, just double click (once for source,
and immediately follow with the destination).  Therefore, dilation and
shear are only described by 2 parallel point movements, where the 0vector
is considered to be parallel to any other vector.  And reflection is
only described by a movement (possibly a 0movement).

For the rotation case, the interface should change slightly.  There is no
need for a destination, so leftclicking once will set the center of rotation. 
Right click will delete it, and leftdrag will move it. 

Note that not all movements will make sense in all circumstances.  For
example, a movement in reflection MUST be in the direction perpendicular
to the reflection line.  Also, dilations and shears can only deal with
parallel movements.  I'm not sure how the user interface should deal with
this.  For reflections, it seems fairly easy: after you click on the
source, the cursor will only move along the line perpendicular to the
direction of the reflection line, even if the mouse is moved in other
directions.  I guess you'd say that the cursor is the "orthogonal
projection" of the mouse position onto the line.  Am I being too unclear?

For dilations and shears, the situation seems more difficult.  Making a
similar restriction (only for the second line, since the first line can be
anything) will make editing data extremely difficult.  Maybe the program
will accept any data and then complain when it tries to implement an
impossible dilation.

In every case but rotation, translation, and reflection, some sets of data
are ambiguous.  For starters, source endpoints can NOT coincide.  For a
shear, the two parallel lines can NOT be of the same length.  For a
dilation, the lines again can NOT be of the same length.  In addition, the
line between the two source points can NOT be perpendicular to the
direction of dilation.

I've got to run, but I'll be back with more comments.

Dan


From dci@math.uchicago.edu Fri Feb  3 10:23:16 1995
