> 
> Wow, I didn't even think about that.  That's really cool.  So each 
> stuntsheet will have predefined local groups for the different symbols 
> and continuities.  To make it even more CS-like, local groups could mask 
> out global groups (so the user just gets one list).  Then you could have 
> a group of men defined on each stuntsheet, except the men in the group 
> are different on one stuntsheet.

I thought you would like this notion.  As a mathematician, the general
idea of unifying separate concepts into one theory is very appealing. 
With the exception of the time when Martin originally conceived the idea
for Calchart, I think that this is the biggest development in calchart
"theory."

I'm not sure what you mean by masking, so please explain in more detail by
giving an example or something.  It seems from what you are saying that
this will solve the problem of having groups that are on more than one
stuntsheet but not ALL stuntsheets.

More thoughts on groups.  Groups should be very flexible.  No reason why
global groups have to consist of the same labels on all sheets.  For
example, there could be a global group for the easternmost line of men in
each formation.  I don't know how this would be useful, but it might be.

Symbol groups should be given the names "PLAIN", "SOLID", "BKSL", etc. as
in the old program.  Global label groups should be given the name
corresponding to their labels:  "A1," "69", "B0", etc.  These groups
should be accessible from the general group menu, but perhaps should not
appear automatically since there will always be many many label groups. 
The program should forbid the creation of any group that coincides with a
symbol group name or a label group name.  It should be impossible for any
man to lie in more than one local symbol group.

ANY local group can have continuity text assigned to it.  Usually, only symbol
groups get continuity text.  This removes the necessity for a separate
command to create a new continuity group.  Just create a new local group
and assign it continuity.

What about global groups getting continuity?  I'll have to think about
what this means.  This could be kind of useful - if you want to specify
unique continuity for 69, you could just put it in 69's label group. 
Maybe this is getting out of control.

Also, what happens when a man lies in more than one local group with
associated continuity text?  There would have to be a rule of precedence
to determine which continuity actually gets applied.  I suppose that
symbol groups have the highest precedence.  There is no need to set
precedence between different symbol groups since they are mutually
exclusive.  After symbol, I guess alphabetical order would work.  After
all, this rule will only need to be applied when the user fucks up and
accidentally redundantly assigns continuity.

What about concatenating continuity in the case of redundant assignment?
Think about this kind of flow, which happens fairly often.  For the first
16 beats, plain and solid do the same thing, but slash and bksl do
something else.  Then for the second 16 beats, plain and slash do the same
thing, but solid and bksl do something else.  This could be implemented by
assigning each man to two continuity texts, which are to be executed in
succession.  But now how is the order of execution defined?  

This would reduce the amount of typing necessary, but would so greatly
increase confusion that I doubt anyone would ever use it.  In fact, I
would probably only use it because I thought it was a cool capability, not
because it was actually more efficient. 
 
> 
> I don't know about this.  Relabeling is a special case (there is one set 
> of labels for the whole show, not one for each stuntsheet).  I suppose 
> that once in a blue moon someone will want to change the symbols for a 
> few men (or a symbol group) throughout the show, but I forsee people 
> trying to use it and screwing up the show and not realizing it for a 
> while (since you don't really see the changes).

Well, I'm thinking about loosening our restrictions on labels.  By
thinking of things in terms of groups, some ideas that seemed originally
cumbersome now become much more natural.  I'm not going to say anything on
it now - you'll have to wait until I have a consistent theory.

Here's just a taste.  We already talked about global label groups.  There
are also two-sheet animation groups which consist of a single man on each
of a pair of consecutive sheets.  These pairings determine origin and
destination for the animation.  Currently, the animation groups are
derived directly from the label groups.  What if that requirement is
dropped?  What about the requirement that animation groups associate men
on adjacent sheets?  What does it mean that man B1 on stuntsheet 3 goes to
man A5 on stuntsheet 31?  What about dropping the requirement that label
groups (or animation groups) are singletons?

Anyway, I'm sure you see the point.  Admittedly, all of this stuff seems
pretty useless, but in the interest of "Generalize!", it might be wise to
actually implement in such a way that it doesn't interfere with normal usage.
We could hide the stuff away in obscure sub-sub-menus if necessary.
 
> 
> Yes, that idea's evil.  Hopefully, this version will help the charting a 
> little (since stunt obviously depends on calchart).  Animating the shows 
> in 3-D should help a lot of things, viewing the certain men in the animation 
> should help block selection (if they care about instrumentation) and 
> these new transformations may help them try new flows instead of doing 
> the same ones.

Another real problem with the difficulty-meter is that it will only
measure difficulty in ways that the programmers thought of.  For example,
one obvious thing is to count the number of pivots required.  Or the
amount of marktime.  But how does one quantify difficulty of alignment, or
the fact that lines are supposed to pop in countermarches?

Let's be perfectly honest about the use of our neat new ideas - they're
really not a whole lot more than toys for stunt and even more for us. 
Really, the old version is perfectly good for everything stunt has to do. 
It's not like the old version is so hard to use that it prevents stunt
from doing its job.
 
> 
> That's probably a little more natural to the user (of course completely 
> different from the old version).

Different from the old version is just fine.  There are so many other
changes that this one won't make any difference.
 
> 
> One thing I was thinking about is that smart move is sort of a special 
> case for the "mesh" action I mentioned before, where you move an 
> arbitrary set of men into a certain shape (for circles or whatever).  
> So maybe you could select the men (in order with the right button I 
> guess) and then somehow define the line and everything gets moved.  You 
> could do the same for circles or maybe even freehand shapes like a 
> phantom mask.  The problem I see is that the order you entered the men 
> isn't really apparent.  I guess to enter the line, you can enter the 
> first point and then the second point in the line and all the men are 
> spaced at that interval.

You hit the nail on the head when you observed that the order of entering
the men is not apparent.  That's why smartmove has to be an exception to
the normal rule of select first, act second.  It defeats the purpose of
smartmove if you have to prespecify the men in the order that you want to
move them.  Smartmove is used mostly when stunt charts scatterflows in
pregame.  They want to be able to make up the order as they go - they
don't want to click on points and then move them all at once.

A lot of this relates to my previous letter on clevermove.  If I were to
implement a circle-locator, this is how I would do it.  I'm not sure on
the exact method of inputting data, but here's an outline.  Define the
circle by locating the center and a "base point" on the circumference. 
This uniquely determines a circle.  alternatively, you could define a
circle by clicking on the center and dragging to set the radius.  However,
even with the mouse method you still need a "base point" on the
circumference.  Next define the interval between men in terms of central
angle; equivalently, specify the number of points to be evenly placed all
the way around the circle.

Now, the first rightclick will zap a man onto the base point.  successive
rightclicks will zap men into position around the circle counterclockwise.
Leftclicks zap men into position clockwise.

As for freehand shapes, there is going to be a very big problem in that it
is EXTREMELY difficult to draw a smooth curve freehand with a mouse.  How
in the world could a user input the shape of a mask?  It would NEVER look
right - it would probably be better to just do it the oldfashioned way.  I
suppose a mask could be constructed piecewise out of smooth curve-makers
that you see in drawing programs.  But then you're going to have trouble
ensuring that the boundary between pieces is smooth.  I see this as a
hopeless obstruction, although it would be really nice to be able to set
the scriptcal in a systematic way.  Any suggestions?

> 
> I don't know if it would be worth it.  As you repeatly use smart move, 
> the program will probably move the two control points to set the next 
> location (I think this is probably the easiest way to write it).  So it 
> wouldn't have any idea where the "negative" is.  Well, actually I guess 
> you could have a second set of control points, so it wouldn't be that 
> hard.  But would it just confuse the user interface?

Algorithmically speaking, smartmove can be implemented like this: when you
click on a point, it gets moved to p1 + n (p2 - p1), and n is incremented
by one.  Notation is the same as in the other letter.  For negative
smartmove, leftclick causes the man to be moved to p2 + m (p1 - p2), and m
is incremented by one.  Note that m and n are independent variables.  This
is very simple, and provides no obstruction to the implementation of
negative smartmove.  The same basic idea can be used for the
counterclockwise/clockwise problem in the circle case.

Dan


From dci@math.uchicago.edu Sun Feb  5 11:25:58 1995
