> 
> I guess this was a miscommunication.  It would be more consistent your 
> way, but not as fast.  I guess since there's a key to do it, it's not too 
> bad.  But you still have to hit this key, move a point, then hit return.

It seems that our positions on this issue have reversed!  You are now the
proponent for "easy usage," and I am the proponent of "consistent
interface."  I can't think of any contradictions with your idea for rapid
translations, so I guess it will work.  However, there should still be an
icon for translation.
 
> 
> Okay, you move the first endpoint outside of the line between the source 
> points.  Then you move the second endpoint to the first source point.  
> Then you move the first endpoint to the second source point.

Either I'm very confused, or we're not talking about the same thing,
because this makes no sense to me.  Here is a very explicit description of
what I am imagining.

There is a block of men centered at the 50.  The user wants to reflect
this block about the 50 (so that the position of the block as a whole does
not actually move).  Being an old-fashioned kind of guy, he doesn't use
the reflection action; he's going to do it with geniusmove.  He selects
the block, and then chooses the geniusmove icon.  Now he clicks on the man
on the north 40 at the hash, and clicks again on the south 40 at the hash
(so a horizontal line 20 yards long appears).  Now, he clicks on the man
on the south 40 at the hash, and clicks again on the north 40 at the hash
(so a horizontal line 20yards long appears).  Finally, he clicks on a man
on the 50, and clicks again on the same point.

Now he suddenly realizes that he actually wanted to reflect about the
south 45, not the 50.  So he wants to edit his data.  But the horizontal
lines are on top of each other.  Even the endpoints coincide.  How can he
clearly communicate to the program that he wants to edit the
southward-pointing vector, NOT the northward-pointing vector?  Simply
using the mouse is impossible; there will have to be some keyboard
solution (use SPACE to select through a series?).

Almost never will this situation actually arise, but sometimes it will. 
Of course, if source points agree and destination points agree, then the
two vectors are identical, so the program should not consider them as
separate data entries.  However, in my example the orientations were
reversed, so the two vectors were NOT the same.
 
> 
> Yes, this can be problem with moving reference points also.  I suggest 
> that the user click on a point that contains several different men and 
> then press SPACE to cycle between them.

This seems to be the only possible solution.  I hadn't thought of the
reference point situation, but you are right that this is a major pain
with the old version.  Especially since refpoints very often coincide.

Come to think of it, this cycling mechanism should apply to individualmove
and to any other similar situation.
 
> 
> Maybe a little cumbersome, but it could be useful.  If you really wanted 
> to simplify things, you could just hit return to go to the next "line" 
> and forget about the cursor and all that.  But maybe the cursor will help 
> the user.

Considering our new implementation, the cursor is a good idea for
oldfashioned smartmove, regardless of clevermove.  Remember that the user
will click on the smartmove icon.  At this time the smartmove cursor
appears.  When the user aborts the smartmove, the icon disappears.

There should be a way to "continue" the most recent smartmove, even after
aborting.

Anyway, clevermove is just an idea.  We can decide about it later.  It's
certainly one of those things that can be added later, since it will be
fairly easy to implement once smartmove already works.  I'd say go for it
in all of its cursors-and-arrow-keys glory, but I don't have to write the
code.  :)  Clevermove will never "get in the way" since it has to be
intentionally invoked by clicking on an icon.

Dan


