Last night I dreamed about calchart.  Minutes of time were like points, and
dreams were the equivalent of groups.  I guess I really have gone ballistic.

I've got a few new ideas.  After writing about orders yesterday, I thought
of a new way to handle nextsheet, previoussheet, movesheet, copysheet,
removesheet, etc.  The user selects "Order," and a vertical listing of all
stuntsheets appears (in the sequence representing the order).  To the side
of the list are a bunch of options: goto, copy, move, insert, delete, etc.
This makes manipulation of stuntsheets much more intuitive since you can
think of it pictorially as adjusting the stack of sheets listed onscreen.
The user can make as many changes as he wants and then presses ESC to abort.

If this sounds good to you, I'll rewrite that section of the outline.

Also, I've been thinking more about what we talked about with how to type
continuity instructions.  The goal really is to allow the user to view
more than one set of continuity instructions simultaneously.  I don't
think that your solution will really accomplish that very well since the
user will still have to scroll up and down.  Besides, it's just so ugly to
have a single text file with special codes to separate the different sets
of instructions.

How about splitting a window vertically (or horizontally) so that the user can
edit two sets of continuity simultaneously?  I don't think there's much
need for more than two, but we could allow the user to request more splits
in order to view more than two continuities at once.  Then, we can keep
each set of continuity as a separate body of text, but it will be easy to
go back and forth between them.

Dan


