From: Dan Isaksen <dci@math.uchicago.edu>
Message-Id: <199502280057.SAA14452@dent.uchicago.edu>
Subject: continuity language improvements
To: gmeeker@uclink.berkeley.edu
Date: Mon, 27 Feb 1995 18:57:10 -0600 (CST)
Cc: dci@dent.uchicago.edu (Dan Isaksen)
X-Mailer: ELM [version 2.4 PL13]
Content-Type: text
Content-Length: 2468      
Status: RO
X-Status: 


At first glance, here are the changes that I think we should make to the
continuity language.

1) Refer to arbitrarily labelled points of arbitrary groups: P(<label>
<group>) is the position of man <label> on group <group>.  Change current
point to CP to avoid ambiguity.  Note that this function has the same value
for all men.

POS(<group>) returns the position of the man under consideration on group
<group>.  Unlike P, POS takes on different values for different men. 

POS is an abbreviation of "position," and P is an abbreviation for "point".

2) Stepsize GV = 1.

3) Fountain takes a stepsize parameter.

4) COMPASS(<point>) returns nearest compass direction (N, S, E, W, NE, NW,
SE, or SW) from CP to <point>.  COMPASSFROM(<point1> <point2>) analogously.

CARDINAL(<point>) returns nearest cardinal direction (N, S, E, or W) from CP
to <point>.  CARDINALFROM(<point1> <point2>) analogously.  Note that this
is a slightly different definition of "cardinal" than the one that we have
been using in our discussions.  "Compass" is equivalent to our old meaning
for "cardinal."  There is a small obvious problem with using the term
"CARDINAL" (ie, stanford).

These functions operate similarly to EITHER.

5) GRAPEVINE <stepsize> <steps> <direction1> <direction2> is the obvious
thing.  Direction1 is the direction of travel; direction2 is the direction
which bandsmen are facing.

FMGV <steps> <direction1> <direction2>.  Same as above, but assumes that
stepsize is 1.

FMGVTO <direction> <destination>.  Obvious.  If direction of travel is NE,
SW, NW, or SW, then stepsize is DM; otherwise, stepsize is GV.

-----------

It may seem that the grapevine commands are irrelevant, but they are going
to become much more important when a nice 3d animation viewer is installed.
Might as well plan ahead and install them now.  I would definitely use
them, but lazy stuntmembers won't bother to do the extra typing and
thinking necessary.

Erin suggested trying to unify the continuity language with the standard
abbreviations used in writing continuity instructions for bandsmen.  Maybe
it would make more sense to change the standard abbreviations to match
Calchart's language?  I fear that this would only increase the
mathematization of charting.  I can easily envision stuntmembers with the
mentality, "But how will I explain this to bandsmen?  The set of standard
abbreviations does not cover this possibility.  Oh, well, I guess I'll try
something else."

Dan


