In fact, I've never compiled an X program before, so this may be very
difficult.  If it's TOO much of hassle for you, then don't worry about it.
 
> 
> If thing worked right, you can just change a couple lines in the config 
> file.  If course, I don't expect stunt to be able to do this, but maybe I 
> can insure that future adm-poops will know how to customize the config file.

> 
> This is already easy to do.  Two lines in the config file.  Should this 
> stuff be in the program itself?  It's currently a remnant of my old 
> non-GUI based program, and left it as is.  But if adm-poop isn't clueful, 
> these features may be lost.

I generally think that it is not a good idea to trust someone to
understand a configuration file.  If you do, then those possibilities that
depend on changing the config file will be lost until some other
programmer comes along and studies the code to figure out how things work.
I don't see any reason not to build these ideas as features.  We can hide
them away in submenus if they seem to be getting in the way of normal
everyday use.
 
> I agree.  I realize that you probably knew more about what was going on 
> then I ever will, but I'd say that I have a good idea of what's going on 
> for an underling.  I'm starting to feel the way you do.  And the power 
> thing is ricidulous.  The Cal Band is really so insignificant in the 
> scheme of things.  That's one reason I'm glad I'm not more involved than 
> I am.  I admit that power attracted me when I was a newman, maybe even a 
> little bit later on.  But the thing I was most hesitant about when 
> running for drum major was the thought of having to make policies for 
> things I don't really care about.  At least now I can try to improve my 
> position in the work force instead of in the Cal Band.

I used to have a motto for dealing with power-mad bandsmen: "It's just a
band."  All of these incredibly important band decisions are actually very
minor in the grand scheme of things.  Only band alumni have the knowledge
to distinguish between good decisions and bad decisions; the other
thousands of audience members can't tell the difference.
 
I am very glad to hear that you have enough foresight to see beyond your
few years at Berkeley.  Unless you are planning on being a band director,
you're going to have to find something to do with yourself for the rest of
your life.  I think that Rune is making a terrible mistake with the
complete disregard he is giving for his academics.  He thinks that being
senior manager is going to pad his resume sufficiently.  I guess it would
impress Jack Brown, but I'm not sure how many other employers are going to
ignore that brilliant 2.3 GPA.

> That wasn't a real poopsheet, but something I put into calchart before I 
