grid size.

Zooming in and out is pretty obvious, I think.

Grid size should always be a power (positive or negative) of 2.  For example,
2 step, 4 step, 1 step, 1/8 step, or whatever.  There is no need for a minimum
gridsize as long as there is no maximum magnification for zooming.  Just
keep subdividing intervals as magnification increases.

The question I am wondering about is: Does grid size change automatically
when you zoom?  Or does grid size always have to be changed manually? 
Seems like a combination of both ideas would be good. 

Grid size does change when magnification changes, but it can also be set
manually.  Once it is set manually, it will stay fixed at that grid size
regardless of subsequent zooming.  When setting grid size, there is an
option for "auto size."  This would be the way to turn off a manually set
grid size and return to automatic grid sizing.  Does this make sense, or
have I described it poorly again?

Dan



From dci@math.uchicago.edu Fri Mar 10 11:00:16 1995
Received: from math.uchicago.edu (math.uchicago.edu [128.135.72.38]) by pasteur.EECS.Berkeley.EDU (8.6.10/8.6.4) with ESMTP id LAA12584 for <gmeeker@volga.EECS.Berkeley.EDU>; Fri, 10 Mar 1995 11:00:15 -0800
Received: (from dci@localhost) by math.uchicago.edu (8.6.10/8.6.10) id NAA15919 for gmeeker@volga.EECS.Berkeley.EDU; Fri, 10 Mar 1995 13:00:33 -0600
From: Dan Isaksen <dci@math.uchicago.edu>
