> Okay, I got this wrong again.  I payed a little closer attention to 
> calchart and I definately won't be able to do scroller exactly like 
> that.  When you get to the edge and you move the mouse a little further, 
> the pointer doesn't move, but the screen scrolls.  In a window based 
> environment, this is tricky (if even possible) to implement and it makes 
> moving to other windows impossible without some other action.  What I 
> could do is define a thin region around the window where if the pointer 
> is on top of, the screen will scroll.  Maybe even make the region almost 
> the entire window, with the center no moving at all and the edges moving 
> really fast.  This would be disabled if the whole field fits into the 
> window.  Now that I think about it, the region should definitely not be 
> on the field, as clicking on points would be annoyingly difficult.  But 
> there should definately be a range of scrolling speeds.  So maybe just a 
> 1/2" border or so?  The further off the field the pointer is, the faster 
> it scrolls.  The field would end up moving a little bit when you move the 
> pointer outside the window, but this shouldn't be too bad.  Well, that's 
> about the best thing I can think of at the moment.

I hadn't thought of the trouble with switching windows.  Yes, this is very
severe.  I wonder why we didn't think of this before?  It goes to show
that you can make all the plans you want, but when you actually get down
to starting the work, there will be difficulties that you didn't expect.

I would prefer having the border be part of the view of the field, rather
than some grey strip at the edge of the window.  This would maximize the
amount of field viewed at any one time.  Also, I think it would have a
more natural feel for the user.  However, this is going to be trouble
because you would have to cross the border to get to the icons and
pulldown menus and so forth.  Maybe there could be a grey strip on top,
but on the sides and bottom the border is part of the view?  I don't
really like the sound of that, either.  This is a tough one.

Here is a variation on your idea of scrolling at different speeds.  The
border is split into two sections.  If you move the mouse into the inside
section, the screen will shift by some discrete amount (8 steps?), but
that's all it will do.  If you move the mouse into the outside section,
the screen will continuously scroll until you pull the mouse back or the
edge of the field is reached.  I like the idea of the discrete amount
because sometimes you want to adjust the view very accurately so that you
can get the whole block on the field, even though it just barely fits. 

If you pass entirely out of the window, you will have caused
some scrolling on the way there.  When you enter a new window, that "exit
scroll" will be undone, so there won't be any annoying scrolling every
time you switch windows.  However, if you reenter the same window, then
the "exit scroll" will not be undone.  This deals with the situation when
you wanted to scroll, but you accidentally put the mouse out of the window.
On your way into a window, the scrolling is disabled.  To change windows
and scroll, you would have to move the mouse into the center and then pull
it back to the scrolling border.

I think the only way to really figure out what to do is to write some code
and give it a try.  I'd be more than happy to give you my opinion.

Dan


