> This, however requires stunt to think ahead.  I personally don't think 
> that practicing pregame backwards helps much.  It is good to have pregame 
> and halftime face the same way, but I think doing pregame backwards at 
> Edwards is weird for most people.  At a strange stadium, it doesn't 
> matter.  You just tell the band that some direction is north and you do 
> both shows that way.  What's weird is if you switch the directions 
> between pregame and halftime.  For some reason we did that at fUCLA this 
> year.  Halftime was performs to the pressbox there and home.  But I think 
> they wanted the script cal to the pressbox.  I can't remember if this is 
> the way things usually are, but I think they might be.

The situation you describe is exactly the one case where the orientations 
get confusing.  It happens when you want to do a show twice, when the 
second time the orientation of halftime switches relative to the orientation
of pregame.

Does this discussion have any relevance to Calchart design?  Maybe there 
ought to be a "reverse orientation" feature that turns the whole show 
upside-down and also adjusts the continuity.  Actually, there should be 
two routines, one for flipping about the north-south center line and one 
for rotating 180 degrees about the midpoint of the 50yard line.

Dan


