> A related problem is that the end zones are handled.  Full field spread 
> for a 169 wedge goes into the end zones, so it's definately useful.  
> Right now, the border around the field is part of the field mode, but I'm 
> realizing that this would be cumbersome if things need to be changed.  
> For instance, in spring show, it's possible that stunt would want to 
> chart people off in the wings.  Also, tunnel flow could be charted off 
> the normal field so that the yard lines are automatically printed 
> correctly.  But the interface is a problem.  Not only for scrolling to 
> these other regions, but also for the animation window.  I guess for 
> animation, anything outside a certain region could be clipped off.  But 
> that's not very desirable for tunnel.  Print will also be a problem, 
> mainly because a lot of that is hard-coded.  I wrote that stuff way 
> before I planned to rewrite calchart, so I wasn't planning on the size of 
> the field changing.

I don't see how the animation is much of a problem.  You could add 
scrolling to the animation when necessary so that all the points can be 
seen, even though perhaps not all at once.

Here is my suggestion for interface design to deal with this problem.  
There will be variables defining the north, south, east, and west 
boundaries of the viewable region.  In the current version, these 
variables are fixed at 10N, 10S, 10W, and 10E respectively.  My 
notation "nX" means "n yards beyond the X side of the field".

If you move a point off the field, then the variables get changed
automatically so that there is always a 10yard zone around the outside of
the viewable region without any points in it.  The viewable region can
expand AND contract automatically in this way, but it never gets smaller
than the full field plus 10 yards on all sides. 

The user can manually set these variables if he so desires.  The values 
can be typed in directly.  Is there a good way to allow for graphical 
definition of these values?  Selecting a region, or something?  I can't 
think of anything satisfying.  There should also be an easy way to return 
to the "normal" situation.

Once the user manually sets values, the automatic method will never 
contract the region beyond those values.  However, it will expand as 
necessary (and contract after expansion, as long as it doesn't drop below 
the manually set values).

Negative values for the variables are allowed.  This would have the 
effect of preventing you from scrolling to all parts of the field.  I'm 
not sure why you would want to do this, but it should be possible.  In 
this case, the automatic method neither expands nor contracts.

There are two constraints: [north] + [south] > -100 and [east] + [west] >
53 1/3.  The program will not accept data violating these values.

Strictly speaking, it could be possible to allow for data violating these 
constraints.  This would have the effect of reversing the orientation of 
the display so that north is to the left, or whatever.  But I don't see 
any reason to allow for this.

Dan


