I forgot to get XKeysymDB before, but now I have done it.  Things work 
much better.  Both backspace and delete work fine.  Also, all the warning 
messages no longer appear.
 
> > 9.  (XV) There is an ambiguity in the name "Show info".  Do you mean it 
> > as an adjective and noun (ie, "information pertaining to this show")
> > or do you mean it as a verb and noun (ie, "put the information on the 
> > screen")?  Can we think of a non-ambiguous synonym?
> 
> Agreed.  Nothing comes to mind right now.


 
> > 12.  You can't undo immediately after an undo.  Why not be able to undo 
> > an undo operation?  Or do something like emacs and be able to undo the 
> > last n operations.
> 
> This shouldn't be too hard, but I'm not sure about the interface.  The 
> undo operations are keep in a stack, so I can't just add an undo to the 
> top because you wouldn't be able to undo more than one operation.  Emacs 
> gets around this by forcing you to do the undo's without anything 
> inbetween.  Maybe there should be another option to undo an undo.

I think a separate option for unundo would be just fine.
 
> > 18.  Although the set of possible locations for points is theoretically
> > infinite, the region that you are capable of seeing is bounded by the size
> > of your monitor.  If a point lies over your "horizon", you can never get
> > it back.  Of course, there's no way to get the points over your "horizon"
> > in the first place.  Or is there?  I have found two ways.
> > 
> > Let's say you add 1000 points and choose to have only one point per 
> > row.  This will create a really long line along the south endzone.  It 
> > will spill far off the field, and probably off the screen unless you have 
> > a very big window. 
> > 
> > The other way is to use block move.  Blockmove a line of points by 
> > indicating where one end will go.  It is possible to manuever the other 
> > end over the horizon.
> > 
> > If you use the second trick on the top edge of the window, the points 
> > will be displayed as piled up along the edge of the window.  Although 
> > they are displayed there, they aren't actually there.  Their actual 
> > location is exactly where they ought to have been translated into the 
> > "negative" region of the plane.
> > 
> > You may wonder how I know what their actual location is when they are off 
> > in unviewable "negative land".  If you block select points and your 
> > rectangle spills out of your window, it affects the selected region even 
> > if it isn't displayed.  I used this fact to gain information about the 
> > locations of the undisplayed points.  Pretty clever, huh?
> > 
> > I think the ideal solution to this problem is this.  When points are very
> > far away from the football field, the scrolling routines should recognize
> > this and allow you to scroll that far.  This solution still provides for
> > the theoretically infinite plane, which is a nice thing.  And it avoids
> > the obstruction of the "horizon" that I talked about. 
> > 
> > One problem with this suggestion is that it still is not easy to put a 
> > point very far away.  (Don't ask why you would ever want to set a point 
> > out in the parking lot outside the stadium :) )  There should be a way to 
> > tell the scrolling routines to let me go a certain prescribed distance, 
> > even though there aren't points out there yet.
> 
> A related problem is that the end zones are handled.  Full field spread 
> for a 169 wedge goes into the end zones, so it's definately useful.  
> Right now, the border around the field is part of the field mode, but I'm 
> realizing that this would be cumbersome if things need to be changed.  
