I think that the general solution to the problem is to have the following 
"attitude" about continuity list management.  The technical details will 
become obvious once we think about things the right way.

A continuity should be deleted if and only if it has no men assigned to 
it AND it has no text (excluding whitespace).  I think that this answers 
all of your questions and scenarios.

A continuity should be created whenever men are changed to a symbol whose
contniuity group does not exist AND there are not already men with that
symbol.  What I'm saying is this.  If all the men are plain, all the men
are assigned to PLAIN continuity, and no other continuities exist; then
when you change some men to solid, the SOLID continuity is created.  If
the SOLID continuity already exists, then changing men to solid obviously
does not cause the SOLID continuity to be created.  If some men are plain
and some men are solid, and all the men are assigned to PLAIN continuity; 
then changing more men to solid does NOT create the SOLID continuity. 

I'm not entirely clear yet on the proper way to implement this strategy.  
You seem to be asking the following question: when should the program do 
a check to see if any continuities should be deleted or created?  The 
answer (I think) is: when the number of points is changed; when a symbol 
is changed; when a continuity assignment is changed; when a continuity is 
selected for editing in the continuity editor.  This covers all instances 
of actions that might affect the existence of a continuity group.

The symbol continuities should definitely appear at the top of the list 
in the "standard" order: PLAIN, SOLID, SLASH, etc.  Funny how I think 
about continuity group names in caps.  The other continuities should 
appear at the end of the list.

Undo sounds trickier to work with.  But this seems like it is really part 
of a broader question concerning undoing changes to text.  I suppose the 
thing to do is to consider all of the editing since you selected the text 
window as a single action - an undo will restore the text to its form 
before you started editing it.

I feel that an undo operation should return the program to its status 
before the action had been taken (or as close to the original status as 
possible).  So undoing an automatic continuity group deletion should also 
undo the action that caused the deletion, since these two occurrences are 
really a single action.

Dan
 
> So I need to figure out how to deal with the list of continuity.  
> Ideally, it would always have continuities the symbols currently on the 
> sheet and empty continuities would automatically be deleted.  This seems 
> very complicated, however, so I need to really think this through.  Okay, 
> it seems there are two parts to this: adding new continuities and 
> deleting continuities.  I think the only time a new continuity needs to 
> be added is when a symbol is changed.  When a symbol is changed, any 
> empty continuities that aren't being used should be deleted.  Setting the 
> number points in a show could affect this also, and undo may be a little 
> complicated.  Another thing, should the list be sorted so that the 8 
> standard continuities are at the top?  Oh, setting the continuity for 
> points could also delete continuities.  For undo, I think it might be 
> easier to put separate entries into the list.  So the first time the user 
> picks undo, the deleted continuity is added back, and the second time the 
> symbols are changed back.  But that's probably going to confuse people.  
> I will have to make some changes to implement the redo option, so I could 
> add something to handle this then.  Anyway, does this sound intuitive?  
> Can you think of anything else that might need to change this continuity 
> list?  Sorry my thoughts aren't very organized.
> 
> Wait, I just thought of a scenario.  What if all the points are plain, 
> and then the user sets all of them to a new continuity.  The plain 
> continuity gets deleted.  What if the user then wants to set one to the 
> plain continuity.  Maybe the 8 standard ones should always be there.  But 
> I like having a list that shows which ones are actually being used.  
> Maybe the user should have to set the symbol again.  Oh, I just realized 
> that "Delete continuity" should make sure that it isn't being used.  Or 
> maybe it shouldn't really delete it but just erase the text so it will 
> get deleted automatically when it isn't in use.  This is getting complicated.
> I think I'll fiddle around with the old version a little, even though it 
> does things completely differently.


From dci@hog.uchicago.edu Sun Jul  7 18:30:29 1996
