> That makes sense, but I didn't do it this way yet.  I'll correct it.  But 
> it now creates and assigns the continuities automatically.  It doesn't 
> delete them automatically, but it checks to make sure that the continuity 
> isn't in use.  So it's pretty usable.

I am probably more proud of the autocontinuity design than of anything 
else about the program except for geniusmove, of course.  It is amazingly 
good at second-guessing what the user is thinking.  In fact, I can't ever 
recall a situation where it did the "wrong thing" and it screwed me up.

This was the way in which I influenced Version 2.  I wrote virtually no 
code, except for a few obvious bug fixes that were not much more than 
typos.  But I did design the way in which a lot of the user interface 
worked, and I invented almost all of the continuity language beyond the 
basic "MARCH" and "MT" and so forth.
 
> Another question... how to deal with case.  The old calchart made 
> everything upper case.  I'm mainly talking about continuity names (because 
> it searchs the names for a string like "PLAIN").  Currently, the user can 
> enter either case, but the search is case-sensitive.  So "Plain" won't be 
> detected as a continuity for plainmen.  I see three options:
> 1. Leave it the way it is.
> 2. Convert the user's entries to upper case.
> 3. Make the search case-insensitive.
> The automatically created continuities are upper case, so maybe 2 is 
> good, but 3 might be okay.  1 is probably not intuitive to users, but it 
> was easiest.

1 is out of the question.  There are more than 100 billion alphabetic 
strings of length 8 or less; there is no need to allow for upper and 
lower case also!  So 2 or 3 HAS to be be done.

The main point for me is to rule out the problem that arises when someone 
types "plain" but really means "PLAIN" and the program doesn't recognize 
this as a distinguished symbol-associated continuity group.  After 
avoiding this kind of problem, my only remaining concern is for what 
looks good.  Is it easier to read all uppercase or all lowercase or just 
capitalize the first letter?  I believe that just capitalizing the first 
letter would be more consistent with the rest of the program.

So my final analysis is to make everything case-insensitive, but the 
programs displays the names as "Plain".  That is, "PLAIN" and "plain" and 
"pLaIn" all mean "Plain", but the pulldown list of continuities looks like

	Plain
	Solid
	X
	Slash
	Sl
	Bksl
	Solsl
	Solbksl	
	Solx

Is there any reason to change these standard abbreviations?  I don't see 
why.  Martin chose them originally to be short yet memorable.

Dan



