>    I've been thinking about a lasso to select points in addition to the 
> current box method.  I'm thinking about which algorithm to use.  
> Basically, the user will draw a blob that will really be a polygon (I'll 
> probably also allow a polygon to be input by specifying each endpoint.)  
> So there are really two algorithms for filling polygons.  The difference 
> is as follows:
>    Imagine a polygon that's a five-pointed star, so the edges cross each 
> other.  One algorithm will fill in the middle region, while the other 
> will not.  This is a minor detail, since I don't think most people will 
> think this way.  I can't at the moment think of how this could really be 
> useful, so unless you see something I'm missing I'll probably just do 
> what's easiest (which will probably be the one that leaves the region 
> unfilled, since that's the more common algorithm).

We had talked about lassoing long ago as a way of selecting points.  
Certainly it would be useful.

As far as your algorithms are concerned, I think I understand the 
difference, but I'm not sure.  When you draw a closed curve in the plane 
(that possibly crosses itself), there always results exactly ONE 
unbounded component.  The first algorithm selects all the regions except 
for the unbounded one.  

Now there is always a way to color the regions alternately black and 
white, like a perverted checkerboard.  The second algorithm only selects 
the black regions (where white is the color of the unbounded component).

Is this a correct mathematical description of the differences?  My 
opinion is that this is irrelevant.  Anybody messing around with 
5-pointed stars deserves to the confusion that results.  So whatever you 
want is fine.
 
> Another thing about making selections...  Right now, you have to shift 
> click on a selected point to move it.  It might be better have a regular 
> click on it move it.  But then how do you unselect points?  I think we 
> decided that the right button should be for genuis move type stuff, but I 
> don't remember.  I'll look at your old messages, but basically I need to 
> change what I've implemented because it's cumbersome.

I'll have to play around with this for a while before I have an opinion.

Dan



