> Another thing about making selections...  Right now, you have to shift 
> click on a selected point to move it.  It might be better have a regular 
> click on it move it.  But then how do you unselect points?  I think we 
> decided that the right button should be for genuis move type stuff, but I 
> don't remember.  I'll look at your old messages, but basically I need to 
> change what I've implemented because it's cumbersome.

I don't fully understand you.  If you left click on a man and drag it,
this causes an individual move.  If you shift left click on a man and drag
it, this causes a block move.  If you left click on an unoccupied point
and drag, this causes rectangular selection.  If you shift left click on
an unoccupied point, this causes "additive" selection. 

If a single man is selected and you want to move it, then you can shift 
left click in order to do a block move (where the block consists of a 
single point).  Or you can left click, which causes the man to be 
unselected for an instant, then immediately reselected, then moved 
individually.

If a bunch of men are selected, but you only want to move one of them, 
then left click deselects all the men, reselects the one you want, and 
moves it.

My "mental picture" of the system is as follows.  There is no such thing 
as an individual move.  When you move a single man, you are really moving 
a block of order 1.  This picture makes the functioning of the program 
perfectly clear to me.

This system seems to be working fine for me.  The only problem is the
annoyance and delay associated with the excessive screen refreshing.  I am
becoming more and more convinced that the screen refreshing trouble is
going to be a huge pain in the ass for users; this is certainly the most
significant problem that I have encountered so far in testing.  If its
solution is a major project, then I suggest you deal with it sooner rather
than later. 

Dan



