> does what most people will want, but it isn't very flexible.

How about a pair of buttons to choose between Standard Labels and Custom 
Labels.  There will also need to be an Edit Labels window.
In the window is a list of all the labels (just like in the 
point selector).  However, you can textedit the lines of this list.  
Changes should NOT be immediate; there should be a Cancel button and a 
Change Labels button.  The Cancel button resets the text in the list to 
match what the labels actually are.  And the Change Labels button changes 
the labels to whatever is in the list.

There is another way to do this.  I have been bothered for a while by the 
fact that the functions of the Information window are a bit random.  They 
don't really have anything in common, other than that the data is 
relevant to all sheets and there is no better place to put them.

Maybe the time has come for a separate Labels window.  Here is a full 
description of what I am imagining.

1) A list displaying all the current labels; the text in this window is
editable, and the lines are selectable.  I'm not sure how the mouse
controls are going to work here.  Maybe there has to be a pair of those 
diamond-shaped buttons in order to choose between Edit and 
Select.  Or maybe single clicking to move the cursor and double clicking 
to select the line.

2)  Another list displaying the letters of the alphabet, which are
selectable as in the current Information window.

3) A Numbers button; when you click on this, the selected labels are
changed to an increasing sequence of numbers, but skipping numbers that
are used elsewhere on the list.  The labels in the main window are not
affected (yet).  Note that it is possible to change only some of the 
labels to numbers while leaving the rest alone.  Usually, this feature 
will be used after ALL the labels have been selected.

4) A Letters button that works similarly and whose specific function
depends on the status of the letter list. 

5) A pulldown menu called Points with two options: Add Points and Delete 
Points.

6) The Add Points option works in just the same way as the current method. 
Dialog boxes asking for the number of points to be added, for
verification, and for the number of points per column.  The labels for the
new points get set to the lowest numbers that are not already taken.  For
example, if you add points to a letter-labeled show, the new points will
be labelled 1,2,3, .... If you add points to a number-labeled show, the
new points will be labelled 145, 146, 147....  Custom labelling may result
in the new labels skipping around; they could be 1,3,5,7,... if the even
numbers are already being used. 

7) The Delete Points option deletes the points whose labels are selected 
on the label list.  Of course there should be a dialog box for 
verification first.

8) A Change Labels button which causes the changes made to the label list 
to take effect in all the other windows.

9) A Reset List button which undoes all the changes made to the label 
list since the last time that the the Change Labels button was selected.

10) A Close Window button.

Perhaps 3, 4, 8, and 9 should be located on a Labels pulldown menu.

Empty labels are allowed (and even conceivably useful!!), but only after 
a warning message.  Duplicate labels are also allowed (and even 
conceivably useful!!), but only after a warning message.

The Labels window takes care of all the old functions of the Information 
window except for comments and field format.  We can create a new 
Comments window, and we can stick field format somewhere by itself.

I see this new idea as an improvement over the old one.  First, it 
integrates custom labelling in an obvious way.  Second, it emphasizes 
correctly the difference between adding points and deleting points.  They 
really are different processes, in the same way that inserting sheets and 
deleting sheets are different.  Third, it makes it easy to delete the 
points you want, not just the points at the "end of the list".

But there is one disadvantage.  Is "proliferation" of windows becoming a 
problem?  Are we ending up with the same kind of interface as Version 2, 
except that you use the mouse instead of the keyboard?

We should probably be evaluating this on a case-by-case basis.  In this 
situation, it seems to be appropriate.  Almost all the time, the Labels 
window will only be used when first creating a new show.  Then it is gone 
forever.  Only special circumstances (changing the number of points, 
changing from numbered labels to lettered labels, custom labels, etc) 
will require additional use of this window.  So it won't clutter up the 
workspace in the same way that the animation window, the continuity 
window, and the point selector window might.


On a slightly related issue, last year in our out-of-control technical 
discussions about Version 2, we fixed the term "point" to refer to a 
field location and the term "man" to refer to a circular symbol with a 
label.  This sounds pedantic, but it is going to become very important 
when you try to write an intelligible manual.

I have noticed that you are using the word "point" to refer to a circular 
symbol with a label.  If it weren't for the accusations of sexism, I 
would encourage you to change to "man", since it is the obvious 
generalization of "plainman", "solidman", etc.  Is there another word 
that we can use that will be more acceptable?  If not, then we will have 
to think up another word for field location.  I guess "location" would 
work for that.

Dan


