From dci@hog.uchicago.edu Fri Jul 12 18:34:08 1996
Received: from hog.uchicago.edu (hog.uchicago.edu [128.135.72.46]) by pasteur.EECS.Berkeley.EDU (8.6.11/8.6.4) with ESMTP id SAA29075 for <gmeeker@volga.EECS.Berkeley.EDU>; Fri, 12 Jul 1996 18:34:07 -0700
Received: (from dci@localhost) by hog.uchicago.edu (8.7.5/8.7.5) id UAA22549; Fri, 12 Jul 1996 20:34:23 -0500 (CDT)
From: Dan Isaksen <dci@math.uchicago.edu>
Message-Id: <199607130134.UAA22549@hog.uchicago.edu>
Subject: Re: Implementing FOUNTAIN
To: gmeeker@volga.EECS.Berkeley.EDU (Garrick Meeker)
Date: Fri, 12 Jul 1996 20:34:22 -0500 (CDT)
Cc: dci@hog.uchicago.edu (Dan Isaksen)
In-Reply-To: <Pine.ULT.3.91.960712153251.6347A-100000@volga.EECS.Berkeley.EDU> from "Garrick Meeker" at Jul 12, 96 03:44:03 pm
X-Mailer: ELM [version 2.4 PL25]
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=US-ASCII
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Status: RO
X-Status: A

 
> I was just thinking about how to implement the FOUNTAIN command.  Because 
> of complicated situtations (like if the result is to go NW and then S) I 
> think I need to use some math instead of just brute force.  I was 
> thinking of doing this:

Well, I think brute force is actually the way to go.  However, more 
sophisticated techniques will make the calculation of the nasty formulae 
easier.
 
> Put unit vectors of the two directions into a 2x2 matrix (M).  The 
> resulting vector is v and the scalors are in u.
> 
> So we have: Mu = v
> 
> We want u so:
>      -1
> u = M  v
> 
> I would invert M with gaussian elimination, right?

See below for a formula in the 2 x 2 case.
 
> So if M isn't invertible, then the directions are either the same or 
> opposite, and we can check to see if it's possible to get there easily.
 
In this case, most of the time it will not be possible to reach the 
desired point.  However, sometimes it will be.  In this case, there will 
generally be infinitely many ways of getting there.  The only time that 
there is a UNIQUE solution is when the two vectors in M are exactly equal 
(same direction AND stepsize).

> Is this how the old version of calchart does this or is there an easier 
> way I'm missing?

This is basically the way that the old calchart does it.

Here is a more methodical explanation of how things work.

I believe that we decided on the format for the fountain command:
	FOUNTAIN <dir1> <step1> <dir2> <step2> <point>

Let u and v be the vectors determined by the first four variables:
	u = ( <step1> cos <dir1> , <step1> sin <dir1> ) = (a, c)
	v = ( <step2> cos <dir2> , <step2> sin <dir2> ) = (b, d)

Let w be the vector given by the displacement from the current position 
to <point>:
	w = (e, f) = <point> - P

We need to find scalars g and h so that:
	w = g u + h v

Once we have calculated g and h, then the marching instructions are:
	MARCH <step1> g <dir1>
	MARCH <step2> h <dir2>

Now we calculate g and h.

Let M be the matrix with columns u and v:
	    | a b |
	M = | c d |

Let x = (g, h).  Then we want:
	w = Mx

Thus the desired formula is:
	x = M^{-1}w

In particular, M must be invertible.

Now for a more concrete description of the solution.
The condition that M is invertible is the same as the condition that u 
and v are linearly independent, which is the same as saying that they are 
not colinear (the angle between them is not 0 nor \pi).  The easy way to 
check for invertibility is to see whether the determinant det M is nonzero.  
The formula is:
	det M = a d - b c

If a d - b c is zero, then the routine is either not possible or possible 
in infinitely many ways.  In either case, you will have 
to produce an error message.

The easy way to calculate the inverses of 2 x 2 matrices is the following 
formula:
	       -1      1
	| a b |   = ------- |  d  -b |
	| c d |     ad - bc | -c   a |

Note that the denominator is just det M.

To be completely concrete, the final answer is:
	     de - bf         af - ce 
	g =  ------- ,  h =  -------
	     ad - bc	     ad - bc

These last two formulae are all the program really needs to know.  The 
need for checking the determinant becomes obvious because it appears in 
the denominators.  I don't see any reason for using sophisticated matrix 
arithmetic libraries (if such things exist for C); just type in the 
formulae directly.

There is one situation in which the degenerate case (det M = 0) actually 
makes sense.  This happens when u = v and w is a multiple of v.  Let N be 
the matrix with columns w and u:
	    | e a |
	N = | f c |

Then w is a multiple of v if and only if det N = 0.

Hence, the degenerate case makes sense precisely when:
	a = b, c = d, ec - af = 0.

To understand this condition intuitively, note that the formulae for g 
and h look like 0/0.  As a general rule of thumb in mathematics, always 
expect weird things when you see 0/0 (or \infinity - \infinity).

When the degenerate case makes sense, then the formulae for g and h are:
	g = e/c, h = 0.

There are other versions of these formulae, but they are all equivalent.

For arbitrary n x n matrices, there is no nice formula for determinants. 
Then you have to resort to something like Gaussian elimination or other
various fancy algorithms.  A lot of people have spent a lot of time
investigating fast algorithms for matrix inversion.

I guess this answer is about 1000 times more thorough than you had 
expected.  Or maybe you have come to expect this kind of thing from me.

By the way, my latest project is to think about the various ways in which 
one can lace shoes.

Dan



