From dci@hog.uchicago.edu Sun Jul 14 14:35:52 1996
Received: from hog.uchicago.edu (hog.uchicago.edu [128.135.72.46]) by pasteur.EECS.Berkeley.EDU (8.6.11/8.6.4) with ESMTP id OAA20504 for <gmeeker@volga.EECS.Berkeley.EDU>; Sun, 14 Jul 1996 14:35:51 -0700
Received: (from dci@localhost) by hog.uchicago.edu (8.7.5/8.7.5) id QAA24469 for gmeeker@volga.EECS.Berkeley.EDU; Sun, 14 Jul 1996 16:36:08 -0500 (CDT)
From: Dan Isaksen <dci@math.uchicago.edu>
Message-Id: <199607142136.QAA24469@hog.uchicago.edu>
Subject: Re: Implementing FOUNTAIN
To: gmeeker@volga.EECS.Berkeley.EDU (Garrick Meeker)
Date: Sun, 14 Jul 1996 16:36:08 -0500 (CDT)
In-Reply-To: <Pine.ULT.3.91.960712203438.8837A-100000@volga.EECS.Berkeley.EDU> from "Garrick Meeker" at Jul 12, 96 08:55:39 pm
X-Mailer: ELM [version 2.4 PL25]
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=US-ASCII
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Status: RO
X-Status: A

 
> The current format is:
>    FOUNTAIN <dir1> <dir2> <point>
> The stepsize should be added, but it does make a slight problem (I think 
> I mentioned this before).  Because the arguments are only separated by 
> white space the following is ambiguous:
>    FOUNTAIN 90 - 1 180 - 1 NP
> Does this mean:
>    FOUNTAIN (90 - 1) (180 - 1) NP
> or:
>    FOUNTAIN 90 (-1) 180 (-1) NP
> I forget what I make it default to when I ran into this (so it's 
> something I've already taken care of).  If anyone actually were to use 
> arithmetic, they should really use parenthesis.  I'm telling you this 
> because I think this should be mentioned in the manual.  It's a big 
> weakness in the language, technically speaking.

Adding the stepsize doesn't make it any more ambiguous, does it?  It's 
already ambiguous:
	FOUTAIN 180 - 90 NP

Maybe you are envisioning a command that takes either 2 or 4 arguments.  
All of the commands in version 2 have a fixed number of arguments; no 
flexibility in that way.

My suggestion is to require 4 arguments for FOUNTAIN.  If you want a 
two-argument command, then make a new one called FT or FNT or something 
like that.  That fits the general pattern (like COUNTERMARCH vs. HSCM, or 
MARCH vs. FM).

A lot of seeming ambiguities can be solved by a smart parser.  For example,
	FOUNTAIN 90 - 1 180 - 1 NP
only makes sense if you interpret it as
	FOUNTAIN 90 (-1) 180 (-1) NP.
Any other interpretation does not provide 4 arguments.
 
> > For arbitrary n x n matrices, there is no nice formula for determinants. 
> > Then you have to resort to something like Gaussian elimination or other
> > various fancy algorithms.  A lot of people have spent a lot of time
> > investigating fast algorithms for matrix inversion.
> 
> I had forgotten that I could simplify this for 2x2 matrices.  Maybe 
> because I've had to write Gaussian elimination algorithms so many times 
> for graphics classes (when dealing with 3x3 or 4x4 matrices).  I'm glad 
> you reminded me of this before I did it again.  Maybe I should brush up 
> on my linear algebra.

For any given n, there exist such explicit formulae.  However, they get 
very complicated very quickly.  In actual practice, the matrices that 
usually arise tend to have lots of 0 entries.  So if you just use the 
formulae, you will waste a lot of time multiplying by 0 over and over 
again.

Gaussian elimination is advantageous in that it can avoid this 
problem.  It can tell when a matrix is "easy to invert", and does it the 
easy way without a lot of unnecessary work.

However, the 2 x 2 case is so simple that it's just not worth it.
 
> I seem to have deleted the relevant part of your response, but you think 
> that:
>    FOUNTAIN N S NP
> should produce an error if NP is, say, north of P?  I don't know why 
> anyone would do that anyway.

I kept a copy of the response, so let me know if you need another copy.

Here's the trouble with FT N S NP.  Let's say that NP is 8 steps due 
north of our current position.  What should the continuity be?  8 N, 0 S 
looks reasonable.  What about 10 N, 2 S?  Or how about -4 N, 12 S?

Technically speaking, these are all perfectly valid solutions to the 
problem.  If you want to add a "shortest possible path" routine when the 
solution is not unique, then that is fine.  But in this capacity, FT is 
functioning more like DMHS or HSDM.
 
> > By the way, my latest project is to think about the various ways in which 
> > one can lace shoes.
> 
> Sounds interesting.  I'd be interested in the results.

I'll let you know when I've got a proof of my conjecture.

Dan



