> We really should have backwards compatibility, so FOUNTAIN should work 
> with 2 arguments.  There isn't really an technical reason why we can't 
> have it take either 2 or 4 arguments, but maybe it would be easier for 
> the user if there were two different commands.

I am concerned with consistency between the various commands.  If we are 
going to allow FOUNTAIN to take either 2 or 4 arguments, then we should 
allow MARCH to take 1, 2, or 3 arguments.  And so forth.
 
I also highly value backwards compatibility.  We have a slight advantage 
in this situation in that the collection of old data is under our 
control.  One solution would be to write a script to convert all the old 
continuity files by replacing "FOUNTAIN" with "FNT".

The other solution I propose is to allow FOUNTAIN to take 2 or 4 
commands, but not to tell anyone about it.  This will give backwards 
compatibility, but it will not confuse current users, either.

Of course, I don't mean LITERALLY not tell anyone.  There ought to be a 
mention in an obscure part of the manual.

> Now the other thing is that the parser is automatically generated from a 
> grammar file, which is a common this to do.  Without going into too much 
> detail, the parser only looks one token ahead so it has to immediately 
> decide what to do.  This parser generator is designed for things like 
> programming languages where this isn't a problem.  I could write a parser 
> from scratch that would handle this, but it would probably be slower and 
> I think it would be way too much work for something that most users will 
> never run into.  Probably better to document that parenthises should be used.

I don't see what's wrong with dependency on parentheses.  Better to 
require parentheses some of the time than commas all of the time.

> > Here's the trouble with FT N S NP.  Let's say that NP is 8 steps due 
> > north of our current position.  What should the continuity be?  8 N, 0 S 
> > looks reasonable.  What about 10 N, 2 S?  Or how about -4 N, 12 S?
> > 
> > Technically speaking, these are all perfectly valid solutions to the 
> > problem.  If you want to add a "shortest possible path" routine when the 
> > solution is not unique, then that is fine.  But in this capacity, FT is 
> > functioning more like DMHS or HSDM.
> 
> I was thinking of "shortest possible path" in this situation.  But this 
> isn't really necessary.  I mainly just want to do it the same way the old 
> one does.  I assume the old version doesn't allow this?  I suppose I 
> could just check.

I do not remember what the old version does.  Come to think of it, I 
think that "shortest possible path" is probably the right thing to do.  
If you had a command like FT DIRTO(R1) DIRTO(R2) NP, the point on the 50 
might end up with something like FT N S NP.  You wouldn't want to make a 
special continuity just for that point.

Dan



