> change and then pressing delete did nothing, and neither did typing
> in numbers into that little box.  If you can't type and need to use
> the slider/buttons then it shouldn't be a white box that you can 
> click in and highlight the number, otherwise...

I guess I should make it stretch it to the end of the window instead of 
making it a fixed size.  I'll look into typing in the tempo.

> I haven't found a really standard way if you're going to allow multiple
> _File_ names on the command line but none of them are required.  If
> the only choices are a file name and a directory name then it is 
> pretty normal to require a certain order, if there's just one argument
> then to check whether it is a file or directory, if there are two
> then to assume that the first is a file, the second a directory.
> 
> > calchart U:\CALCHART;S:\CALCHART pre96.shw
> 
> This would normally be done the other way around for starters (it is
> pretty standard that if you're specifying a file to be auto-opened
> it should be the first argument).  Other than that I don't quite 
> understand what you have as the first argument--a "PATH"-type 
> string (i.e. it looks for files in those directories in that
> order?)  I've never seen anything like that for Windows programs,
> but then what do I know?  Actually, usually when you have something
> like that it is done more like:
> 	calchart pre96.shw U:\CALCHART
> where pre96.shw is a show that it can find (defined later)
> where U:\CALCHART is the location of the configuration file
> in the configuration file (U:\CALCHART\config) might be
> something like:
> 
> [FILES]
> SHOWS=H:\CALBAND\CALCHART
> PROGRAM=S:\CALCHART
> RUNTIME=S:\CALCHART\RUNTIME

The platform-independent gui library I'm using allowing searching for 
files in multiple directories.  This has a few benefits.  If you're 
creating a new EPS file for a spring show stage in a new location, it 
could find that in your personal directory while all the other postscript 
files would be in the standard place.  It works like the PATH variable.  
I hadn't thought about setting PROGRAM, but I guess I'll need to when it 
looks for the help files.

Two more questions for you guys, since this is something you'll need to 
deal this.  First of all, I'm going to implement an auto-save feature.  
Where should these go?  In the user's home directory somewhere?  I 
suppose this should be configurable, but I'm working if it should be in 
the current directory.

Secondly, how should the location of shows be specified?  Most people 
should have the default place be where all the shows are, so anyone can 
look the the shows that have been finished.  But Stunt and other people 
might want to have their own secret locations?  And you might not want 
people changing shows that have been finished.  Ideas on how this should 
be set up?

-Gurk


