From: Garrick Meeker <gmeeker>
To: dci@math.uchicago.edu
cc: Garrick Meeker <gmeeker>
Subject: CalChart collisions
Message-ID: <Pine.SUN.3.91.960903180001.6953D-100000@c3p0>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII
Status: RO
X-Status: 

Before I get to the real question, I've made some changes I should tell 
you about.  First of all, there is now an initial window with buttons for 
a new window, to open show, or to quit.  This was mainly to get around 
the problem of the whole program exiting when you close the first window, 
but I kind of like it.  Secondly, I've added keyboard shortcuts to the 
menus and buttons.  Under Motif, they show up in the menus, but they 
don't seem to work.  It works under Windows though.  So try it out.  I 
also has more work done on editing reference points.

Now, what should I do about detecting collisions in animation?  I looked 
at the source for the old version and it seems to be done realtime in 
assembly (which I don't have the source to).  I believe that collisions 
are detected as follows:

two points at (a,b) and (c,d) collide iff
(a-c)^2 + (b-d)^2 <= 1 step

The simple algorithm would just check every point against every other, so 
for a blocksize of 160, we would have 160*160/2 checks per beat.  Each 
would involve 2 multiplications (the main time concern here), so for 240 
bpm, we would have 102400 multiplications per second.  For a 25Mhz 
machine, assuming a multiplication takes about 30 cycles, you're already 
using 12% of the CPU time.

That should show the need for a good algorithm.  I've got a few in mind.  
An important step is checking eliminating the multiplications, like if 
|a-c|<=1 or |b-d|<=1.  I was wondering if this was something that you and 
Martin discussed.  It's possible that the old version even calculates 
this ahead of time.  I haven't formally thought about an algorithm (I'll 
probably drag out my algorithms book and see if there's a similiar 
problem) but there might be an O(NlnN) algorithm instead of O(N^2).

I'm not expecting an algorithm out of you, but it'd be nice to know 
everything you know about collisions in the old version.

Gurk


