I think CalChart is finally ready for widespread testing.  Reference 
point editing is functional now, and last night I wrote a simple 
collision detecting algorithm.  I used the short cut to avoid 
multiplications I mentioned in my last mail and a simple algorithm that 
compares every point with every other.  There's no noticable slowdown on 
my machine, but we'll have to see how it works on slower machines.

So I'd like to post a message soon asking for people who want to do 
serious testing of all the features.  I'm assuming that ADM-Poop will 
also help.  I'll need to write short certain portions of the eventual 
manual, like an installation guide, an overview of all the menus and 
buttons, and a user's guide for people familiar with the previous 
version.  I'll also need to write a list of things that should be tested 
and a list of what hasn't been finished or doesn't quite work right.

I'm leaving for Disneyland this weekend, so this won't happen until next 
week.  I was wondering if you might be interested in writing any of 
this.  It'd have to be soon, but it doesn't have to be at all thorough.  
Just enought to give people the idea.  Also, I don't know TeX, so it 
might take me a little longer.

-Gurk

P.S. Don't worry, I won't let Stunt start using yet.  The major functionality
missing is editing printed continuity, and all of the smart/genius moves.



