Well, this is the way it works.  You animate the show with the old 
version of calchart.  You then run a simple C program to produce a bunch 
of scripts (one for each beat - several hundred at least) for POVRay.  
You then run a script that runs POVRay for each frame.  Then it converts 
all the raw pictures to GIF files and finally assembles them into an FLI 
animation.  To record it, I'd play it back on my Amiga (which has a video 
out built-in).

So to do it yourself, you'd have the following obstacles.  First, you 
need a lot of disk space (the scripts delete things as it goes, but I 
think it generally needs in the tens of megabytes of disk space.)  So 
that would probably mean a DOS machine (unless you want to use the Sparc 
at work).  I could compile a DOS version of my program easily.  You 
should be able to get a DOS version of POVRay.  You could probably 
rewrite the scripts for DOS, or get a DOS version of csh or sh.  You'll 
also need to find a program to assemble the FLI animation, but that 
shouldn't be hard.  Finally, you'll need a machine capable of recording 
to video.  I don't know about that, but aren't such things cheap 
nowadays?  I might be able to donate one.  If you need something done 
soon, you could use my Amiga.

Gurk

