> out one method for calculating the location of the press box.  
> Apparently, you sight two objects with the sextant and then read the 
> angle between them.  I need at least the location of the press box, but I 
> might as well take sufficient measurements to locate the coordinates of 
> any seat of the stadium.  I was thinking of these measurements:
> 
> 4 distances from the field edges to the stadium wall (the field should be 
>    centered though).
> displacement of the stadium rim relative to the field.
> 
> There's still some unknowns, like any curvature from the bottom seats to 
> the top seats, and the overhead shape of the stadium (I'm guessing it's 
> not a perfect ellipse) but it's probably good enough.  There's a diagram 
> of the seating that came with my season tickets, so I should be able to 
> figure the rest out.

I think it is safe to assume that the stadium slope is constant.  If that 
is not actually the case, then it is very close and certainly good enough.

>From my memory, it would seem that straight sides capped by semicircles 
in the endzone would be a better (although not perfect) model for the 
stadium than a true ellipse.

If you are really ambitious, then you could approximate with four arcs of
ellipses.  Take measurements for eight points around the base of the
stadium: due north (mouth of the tunnel), due south (mouth of the tunnel),
due west, due east, and in the four corners (wherever, but make it
symmetrical).  You will only have to make three actual measurements (N,
NW, and W) and get the rest by assumed symmetry. 

Also, you will need to make measurements of the tangent to the base of 
the stadium at these points.  At N, S, E, W, we know what they are; but 
in the corners it will be tougher.

Now fit an ellipse to the NE, N, and NW points with the prescribed 
tangents.  Do the same thing for NW, W, and SW; etc.  That should give a 
pretty good model.  It should be safe to assume that the stadium rim is 
the same shape as the stadium base.

I will mail you a diagram if you want.

> Greg Jones suggested that after I get the height of the rim, I should 
> calculate the hang time required for a rim-high baton toss.

Excellent idea.  Throwing speed and hang-time are functions of height 
(and vice-versa).

> From the pressbox along the 50, the field will look like a trapezoid.  
> You can read the angles between the ends of the horizontal lines.  You know 
> the actual length of these lines, so you can get the distance.  You know the 
> actual distance of these lines, so you can use the pythagorean theorom for 
> two equations that can be solved simultaneously for the coordinates of the 
> press box.

I think it would actually be easier to calculate the location of the press
box by taking measurements from the field.  Stand at the east end of the
50 and measure the angle of the pressbox above the horizontal.  Do the
same thing for the west end of the 50.  Now the three points pressbox (P),
east end (E) and west end (W) form a triangle.  You know the length of EW,
and you know the angles WEP and EWP.  The entire triangle is now "known"
by the ASA (angle-side-angle) triangle congruence law.  Use the law of
sines to calculate the length of WP.  Let B be the point directly below P
at field level.  Then BPW is a right triangle; you know the hypotenuse WP
and the angle BWP.  Use the definitions of trigononmetric functions to
calculate BW and BP; this gives you the coordinates of the pressbox
relative to the west end of the 50.  If this doesn't make sense, I can
draw you a diagram and mail it to you. 

You can do the same thing for three other points around the rim of the 
stadium at the southernmost, easternmost, and northernmost points.  For 
the north and south points, use the midline of the field, say at the 
0yardline and the 50yardline.



Now I will go into more detail about finding the eight points around the
base of the stadium.  Stand at the mouth of the south tunnel (A), and
measure the angle between the southwest corner of the field (B) and the
southeast corner of the field (C). Now you have an isoceles triangle ABC, 
where you know BC and the angle CAB.  It is easy to find the altitude of 
the triangle, which gives you the coordinates of A.

You can do the same thing for the eastern, northern, and western points.  
The four corner points are a bit trickier, but the same general principle 
applies: solve a triangle, but this time it is not isoceles.

Let the chosen point in the southwest corner be A, and let B and C be the 
northwest and southwest corners of the south endzone.  Measure at B the 
angle ABC, and measure at C the angle BCA.  You already know the length 
of BC, so you can solve the triangle in the same way that you did for the 
pressbox.



Now I will go into detail about finding the directions of the tangent
lines at the four corner points at the base of the stadium.  Let A be the
southwest corner point.  Choose a point B ten yards (or some known
distance) along the tangent line at A; this will have to be done by eye,
but that shouldn't be too much of a problem.  Let C be the southwest corner
of the field, and let D be the southeast corner.  Measure at A the angle 
BAC.  Measure at C the angle DCA.  This will tell you the relative angle 
of the tangent line to due east-west.

> You can also measure the angle between the edge of the field and the 
> opposite stadium wall and get that distance using pythagorean thm.
> 
> I can't think of a good way to get the other measurements from the press 
> box.  I could place large objects of a known size in the stadium, or I 
> could use stereopsis (taking measurements from two locations in the press 
> box) but it seems better to take this measurements from 4 points around 
> the stadium.

If you want me to explain this again, I'd be happy.  Perhaps the best way 
for me to explain this to you is to draw some diagrams and mail them to you.

Dan



