> I think I've finally got a grasp on how to implement smart move.  I've 
> been trying to follow the model of selecting something and then selecting 
> an action on it.  How to implement smart move in this manner wasn't 
> completely apparent, but I've come up with this.  The program keeps track 
> of the order you select points.  You then drag out a line (defining the 
> first and second locations) and the points are moved along this line.  

This sounds good to me.  One should be able to avoid auto-ordering by 
shift-clicking the points individually.
 
What about the spacing along the line?  The points should be placed with 
the first one at the first endpoint, and then they should progress in 
even intervals towards the second endpoint.  But what is the interval?  
Even spacing is not good because that's not how the Cal Band's charting 
works.  Maybe the default should be 2-step spacing (2-step DM on the four 
major diagonals, of course), with an option for 4-step spacing or even 
spacing or a manually entered number like 1 or 1.768 or whatever.  Or 
maybe there is a graphical way of communicating the spacing, like with 
Version 2.

> This actually is much better than the old method because you can select a 
> group and once and it will guess the order.  If you use the selection 
> rectangle, it will start at the point nearest the first corner.  If you 
> use the polygon or lasso selection (which I just got working) it will 
> also follow the points in the direction of the contours.  This means you 
> could even select something like a figure 8 and have it guess the order 
> correctly.  There will have to be additional constaints on the order 
> between points (like should the order of a block be in rows or columns).  
> There will eventually even be other tools, like circles, splines (smooth 
> curves), blocks (you could change the number of rows in a block easily), 
> and hollow blocks.

Auto-ordering is quite a bit more complicated than this, I think.  The
concern about "rows or columns" is a good indication of the problem.  Of
course, there is no reason to say that rows come before columns or columns
come before rows; it depends on the orientation of the flow.  If you make 
one the default, it will be completely arbitrary and half the time will 
be completely wrong.

Here's my suggestion.  Consider the destination line L.  Project the
source points orthogonally (i.e., perpendicularly) onto L.  The source
points end up being ordered along L; shift them along L to get the spacing
right and the starting position right and so forth.  Obviously, some
points might end up on top of each other after they have been projected. 
To break ties in the ordering, the points that were originally further
from L get placed closer to the head of the line.  Still, there is a
possible tie between pairs of points on opposite sides of the line or
between points that are located on top of one another to start with.  Then
the tiebreaker could be a cointoss. 

The rationale behind this is to emulate what a stunt member does when 
working out a pregame flow.  The usefulness of the orthogonal projection 
is obvious.  The logic behind the first tiebreaker is that you usually 
place the men that have a long distance first and then fit the nearby men 
in later.

I think my suggestion is going to be more useful than following the lasso 
around or whatever.  Those methods seem too arbitrary and don't seem to 
indicate the likely order of points very well.

Dan

PS - I can work up the relevant mathematical formulas if you want.


