I was thinking about something this weekend.  Maybe I should try to sell 
a version of CalChart designed for corps bands (after I finish the real 
version of course).  This was something that Ron Quezon has mentioned to 
me many times.  I looked around the internet and could only find 
references to one such program.  I got a demo.  It was pretty shabby and 
it was selling for $99.  It was basically a drawing program.  No 
animation.  Granted, the market is extremely small.  I'm estimating that 
there are a few thousand high schools with marching bands.  I'd be lucky to 
sell a couple hundred copies.  But $10,000 or so for a couple months work 
sounds cool (I'd probably just strip out a lot of stuff and change the 
name.)  Of course, I'd probably need to deal with distribution hassles 
and advertising.  Do you think this would be worthwhile?  The technical 
aspects should be easy, but the logistical stuff could be a problem.  How 
do you advertise to high school band directors?  How do you cheaply set 
up a phone number that they can order from?  And there's disk 
duplication, manuals, and packaging.  Not to mention I'd probably have to 
register a company name, and then there's all sorts of legal stuff.

Gurk



