> It seems strange that it would suddenly stop working.  Maybe someone 
> installed a different ctl3d32.dll?  I know Rune experimented for a long 
> time to get it to work.  I can disable ctl3d usage from calchart quite 
> easily, but it won't look as nice (at least I'm told).  I guess I'll compile 
> that tonight and put it on the web page.  If Rune doesn't have any ideas, 
> maybe you could install that version tomorrow.

I just checked the modification and such dates for the files in the ctl3d
and ctl3d32 packages and none of them have been changed since I last
installed stuff in July.  The older version (the one in S:\CCHART)
works fine for me, it is just the new version that barfs completely.
I think it might be because of the new path stuff that you added...
Some things think that they need the files to be in the 
WINDOWS\SYSTEM directory.  But Windows on a network install does
not create a SYSTEM directory, and installs the stuff into the
plain WINDOWS directory (presumably to keep the number of search
paths on the network to a minimum).  We ended up with a weird situation
where there is a system directory, but practically nothing is in it
because Windows expects there to not be one there for video purposes,
etc.

That's my best guess at the moment, I don't have time to go into great
depth at the moment.  If you can compile it without that feature 
required that might be good--ctl3d32 is a problematic feature for
lots of programs, and dispensing with the problems might be well
worth the lack of nifty borders on the windows or whatever.

> -Gurk

Rune


