If the old one works, that explains a few things.  I believe that having
the ctl dll in the program directory will cause it to fail.  I have it in
the archive, so if you just unzipped it and tried to run it, that might be
the problem.  Try deleting it and run it again.

If that still doesn't work, I compiled a version that doesn't use ctl3d.
It's on the web page.  Under Windows 95, it actually looks about the same,
but I didn't play with it very long at all.

I'd like to ask another favor.  I'm not sure about the status of the
math coprocessor emulation in the Win32 version.  The older version required
a special windows driver to work.  I installed this on the machine on Brad's
desk, but I think Lydia is also lacking a math coprocessor.  Could you let
me know if it works with out this driver?  It will immediately lock up the
whole system (actually, you might have to click the "New" button first).
You should run "msd" or "qaplus" or something to make sure Lydia is lacking
an FPU.  That's what the wemu387.386 file is, BTW.  It's loaded in the
386Enh section of the SYSTEM.INI file (I don't recall at the moment how I
made this change to just one machine.)

-Gurk

