I haven't forgotten about this issue; I was just thinking about it for a 
while before responding.

> The way I implemented it is you draw a line between the first and second 
> points on the line (not the endpoints) so the length of the line is the 
> spacing.  It seems the most intuitive approach.

I get it.  I misunderstood you the first time.  This is perfectly 
reasonable and useful.
 
> I have a few problems with this.  First, I've been calculating the order 
> as soon as selections are made.  This is better for possible future 
> options like circles.  Your method doesn't address this.  Second, 
> consider a line that should be rotated 90 degrees (sure, you should use 
> the rotate command, but let's pretend we're on stunt.)  If I understand 
> you correctly, you'd get an alternation of the points from the two ends.  
> Or consider a chevron that should straightened out, not projected onto 
> itself.  With the lasso method, you should be able to straighten out 
> just about any shape (which is the most useful part of smart move).  You 
> can also append your selection and it will keep track of the order.

The "correct" way to keep track of the order in which points are selected
is to recognize when an entire block has been selected at the same time. 
There might be a mix of individual selections and block selections in one
series; the order of these selections is remembered, but there should be
no internal ordering within a block until it is necessary.  This causes no
loss of information or ambiguity; it just defers calculations until they
are actually necessary.  I have no way of estimating if this will be a
huge hassle in rewriting code. 
 
Maybe my suggestion is too similar to the way that geniusmove works.  
With another tool, you want something that is more geometrical, less 
mathematical.

Dan



