From: Garrick Meeker <gmeeker>
To: dci@math.uchicago.edu, runes@calband.berkeley.edu
cc: gmeeker
Subject: RenderMan and CalChart
Message-ID: <Pine.SUN.3.91.961028113645.28333A-100000@c3p0>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII
Status: RO
X-Status: 

I read about the first third of the RenderMan book, I played the free 
renderer, and I started hooking stuff into CalChart.  You can now 
directly generate the files to render an animation with POVRay (but you 
still need POVRay and a bunch of UNIX scripts I wrote).  It also has the 
beginnings of a RenderMan interface.  Here's what I've learned.  
RenderMan is nothing more that a description language, like PostScript is 
for 2D.  It says nothing about the rendering technique used, but it is 
quite powerful.  The free renderer uses ray tracing (and optionally 
radiosity which calculates the interaction of light between objects).  So 
I'm not sure it will be any faster than POVRay.  According to the 
documentation, an NT version is out of the question.  But eventually I 
could write a quick and simple RenderMan renderer that only implements 
the features I need for CalChart.  This could be run under Windows.  In 
fact, a few years ago I wrote the beginnings of a realtime 3D engine.  
Well, maybe this is a little more technical than you care about.

In other news, Aaron Glimme and I measured Memorial stadium and took 
photos for texture maps.  We even took photos of Rune in uniform, so 
you'll see 160 little cutouts of Rune sliding around the field.  I 
haven't analyzed the data yet, but I think we got what we need.  We got 
44 points around the base (after taking symmetry into account), but only 
two at the top.  I think it okay to make the shape similiar to the base 
and ignore the curvature from the top to the bottom.  We got some 
questions from the stadium crew and they seemed pretty impressed at the 
concept of 3D calchart.  Rune, what were you saying about the blue prints?

Gurk


