On Thu, 17 Oct 1996, Dan Isaksen wrote:

Sorry I took so long to reply.

> The "correct" way to keep track of the order in which points are selected
> is to recognize when an entire block has been selected at the same time. 
> There might be a mix of individual selections and block selections in one
> series; the order of these selections is remembered, but there should be
> no internal ordering within a block until it is necessary.  This causes no
> loss of information or ambiguity; it just defers calculations until they
> are actually necessary.  I have no way of estimating if this will be a
> huge hassle in rewriting code. 

I think that the method used to select the points should be an important 
clue to the order.  If the lasso is used, the first point should be near 
where the lasso began.  This could be a lot of information to keep 
around.

> Maybe my suggestion is too similar to the way that geniusmove works.  
> With another tool, you want something that is more geometrical, less 
> mathematical.

I think that's a very good observation.  I think a geometrical approach 
is probably going to be more intuitive to most people.  If they can't 
understand genius move, they should at least be able to understand what 
smart move is doing.  Another thing I was thinking about was putting in 
an option to draw lines between points to show the selection order (so 
there's no doubt at all what's happening).  This wouldn't be possible if 
the selection order is calculated later.

Gurk


