> Okay, I see what you're saying.  I'm thinking that, if I have time, it would 
> be better to take lots of measurements along one quadrant.  And I'm showing 
> up 3 hours before the game, so I should be able to do anything I want.  
> Then I can see if the stadium really fits this "sausage" model.

Well, it mostly depends on how much time you have.  The more points you 
take, the better will be the fit.  But it's also more work and perhaps 
harder on the computing.  If you are extra ambitious, you can take 
separate measurements of the rim.  And also take them at several places 
up the side of the stadium to check the slope.  But that's a lot of work.
 
> Okay, I see two problems.  First, I don't know if I'll be able to roam 
> around the field (I didn't ask Greg about getting on the field.)  
> Hopefully, they won't mind.  Otherwise I'll have to use my method.  
> Secondly, after talking to Rune, I don't think you can measure from the 
> horizontal accurately.  You sight two points and measure the angle 
> between them.  I figured out how I can sight the stadium base instead.  I 
> think this is the most accurate way.  If I can, I'll probably use your 
> method (modified) for most of the data, but I'll also go into the press box 
> for a measurement of the exact location of the camera crew (using the method 
> I mentioned last time).

You can probably return to the stadium after the game and roam around.  
But maybe they are stricter about field access nowadays because of the grass.
 
I don't know how a sextant works, but it seems like it should work to 
measure angles above the horizontal.  Just choose a point along the base 
of the stadium, and measure the angle between the pressbox and that point.

There definitely are devices for measuring angles above the horizontal.  
Sailors need to know how high is the noontime sun because that tells them 
their latitude.  Try to get one of those instruments, whatever they are 
called.

The advantage of my method over yours is that you will end up with a pair 
of simultaneous quadratic equations.  These are generally harder to 
solve; it's like finding the points of intersection of two circles - it 
can be messy.  Of course, we are only interested in numerical answers, so 
your method would work.  But it is less aesthetically pleasing to a 
mathematician.  My method relies on finding the intersection between a 
circle and a straight line, which is much easier.

> I'll also need to take my height into account, but that's trivial.  Are 
> you forgetting the height of the base above the field?  I could probably 
> eyeball it, but I might as well measure the base the same way as the rim.

> One problem is finding something to lock onto.  I may need to drag 
> someone along to mark the spot (especially if I take lots of 
> measurements).

You will definitely need some markers or place holders.  Preferably they 
should be about as tall as you.  Other people would be ideal, but you 
could also use directors' ladders or poles or whatever.
 
> P.S. I'm surprised you haven't mentioned joining calchart-discussion.  
> I guess you just figured I'd add you.

You're right; I just assumed that you would add me.  I will make a formal 
request now.  Has anything interested been discussed yet?

Dan



