On Thu, 16 Oct 1997, Dan Isaksen wrote:

> I will get to work on it immediately.  Is there anything in particular
> that you want me to test?  I had talked about testing the continuity
> language; I will do that unless you make some suggestions. 

That's the big one.  Another thing that should be tested is the Undo/Redo
system.  There's a limit on the amount of memory used for the Undo buffer
(defaults to 50K).  At that point, you can't undo all the way to the
beginning.  I tested this briefly, but obviously hitting undo/redo a
couple of times is not the same as when you've been charting non-stop for
several hours.

And don't just verify that correct continuity works.  Try incorrect
continuity and make sure that calchart detects it.

> I'm not confident that I understand what you mean by "linear case".  Do
> you mean that all the original points lie on a single line and all of the
> destination points also lie on a single line?  In that case, it is only
> necessary to move TWO points in order to determine the operation.  Is
> there a fancier interface involving drawing lines and so forth?  Moving
> two points is rather primitive.  It's fine for me, but I'm not sure that
> Stunt can handle it.

Yes, that's what I meant, but I guess it wasn't clear because you haven't
seen the new interface.  In the old one, you move the points then hit
Genius.  In the new one, you click on the Genius move button and then move
three points.  It draws lines for all the movements too.  After you've
entered three, it performs the transformation.  So how is it supposed to
know that you're only dealing with two points?  There could be a different
button for the 2-point case, or a button to click after entering two
points.  I think most people will use the new smart move instead anyway,
which is more intuitive for moving lines with even spacing.  Maybe you
should play with the new interface to get an idea of the direction I've
gone.

> I think you mentioned that you want me to write an introduction.  What
> should be there?  Off the top of my head, I could write the history of the
> project from 1989 until now.  I don't know what else to put in there.  Is
> there any particular philosophy of using Calchart that you want to
> express?  I long ago gave up on trying to convince people not to let the
> capabilities and limitations of the program influence their show designs.

The history is a good place to begin.  In the past I don't think too many
people read the manual, but now it will be available from the program.  So
I'm not completely against preaching a little, but I know it probably
won't have much influence.  Most people will probably only use it for
reference.

You could also do a glossary of calchart terminology.  While bandsmen
should be familiar with some, like stuntsheet, it would be good to have
precise definitions of things like point, reference point, beat (how it's
displayed in animation), etc.

Also you could do an overview of the features and tools to create a show.

Some of the more technical parts I'll have to write, but the more general
stuff could be done by whoever has time first.

To be honest, the manual already has the continuity commands, and that's
probably all that's absolutely required.  I'd say that it's much more
important for you to test the continuity language.  I haven't had time to
do it thoroughly and you're probably the only other person that would be
able to tell if the program's behaving correctly or not.

Gurk



