> 
> That's the big one.  Another thing that should be tested is the Undo/Redo
> system.  There's a limit on the amount of memory used for the Undo buffer
> (defaults to 50K).  At that point, you can't undo all the way to the
> beginning.  I tested this briefly, but obviously hitting undo/redo a
> couple of times is not the same as when you've been charting non-stop for
> several hours.

After a long testing session, I will try to undo all the way back to the
beginning.
 
> Yes, that's what I meant, but I guess it wasn't clear because you haven't
> seen the new interface.  In the old one, you move the points then hit
> Genius.  In the new one, you click on the Genius move button and then move
> three points.  It draws lines for all the movements too.  After you've
> entered three, it performs the transformation.  So how is it supposed to
> know that you're only dealing with two points?  There could be a different
> button for the 2-point case, or a button to click after entering two
> points.  I think most people will use the new smart move instead anyway,
> which is more intuitive for moving lines with even spacing.  Maybe you
> should play with the new interface to get an idea of the direction I've
> gone.

Interestingly, the difference between the 2-point and the 3-point case can
be determined internally without explicit direction from the user.  If all
of the selected men lie on a line, then two moves will already uniquely
determine where THAT LINE must go (even though it is not determined where
other men must go, but that doesn't matter since no other men are
selected).  Of course, the sources of the two moves must lie on the
original line itself, but the destinations can be arbitrary.

This requires checking every time a block is selected whether all the men
are collinear.  This is not bad algorithmically because the first two
points determine a line and the rest just have to be checked.  So it's
linear in the number of men selected.

Provided that the selected points are collinear, then geniusmove doesn't
bother to wait for a third move, provided that the two sources lie on the
line.  If the two sources do not lie on the line, the geniusmove waits for
the third move, which will then determine everything in the usual way.
 
> Some of the more technical parts I'll have to write, but the more general
> stuff could be done by whoever has time first.

Why don't we divide things up between us as we go along?  I will first
work on a historical sketch, but I won't try to make it fit with anything
else, at least for now.  We can patch different sections together later.

After I finish that, we can worry about what comes next.  Anything in
particular that you want to work on?

Dan



