On Fri, 17 Oct 1997, Dan Isaksen wrote:

> 
> First I have some questions about how some features work.
> 
> 
> What do all the different colors mean during animation?

There are the usual colors that show what direction bandsmen are facing.
There's another set of colors for selected bandsmen.  Originally I just
had red, but then I wanted to have different colors for different
directions.  I never worked out a color scheme.

> Is there a way to do additive blocking?  I have forgotten.

You hold down shift.  I was thinking about making additive blocking the
default and having a null selection clear everything.  You also wouldn't
have to hold down shift to do a block move.  I remember discussing this,
but I'll have to go look later.

> Do the middle and right buttons have any function other than polygonal and
> lasso blocking?

The right button advances the beat in the animation, but that's it.  There
are probably shortcuts to be made (definately keyboard shortcuts are
needed) but I've been putting these off.

> What exactly are all the purposes of the shift, control, alt, etc. keys?

Right now, it's just shift to add to the current selection.

> If you call the individual move icon the "first" and start counting to the
> right, I can't figure out what the fourth and sixth icons are for.  Are
> they the ones that aren't installed yet?

I don't recall.  You should get a description in the status bar at the
bottom when you position the mouse pointer over the tool.  One of them is
probably for shearing, which doesn't work yet.  The other ones are smart
move, reflection, rotation, scaling, and genius move.

> Now here are some complaints I have about the user interface.
> 
> 
> Rotation move is virtually useless as it is.  It is impossible to get a
> line to rotate exactly 90 degrees for example, because the angle choice is
> "continuous".  There should be some discreteness so that exact angles can
> be obtained.  For example, as you drag the mouse around, the location of
> the cursor should jump from grid point to grid point (rather than
> continuously) so that the angle also jumps.  If you want very fine angles,
> you can go to a long radius where the choices are closer together.  I fear
> that I have explained this poorly.  I'll try again if you don't
> understand.

Yeah, I know.  Most tools snap according to the current grid, but rotation
should also.  Which reminds me... do you think anything should snap each
point onto the grid?  For instance, reflection will snap the line's
endpoints onto the grid, but the actual points won't pay any attention to
the grid setting.

> I hate having to select individual move if I want to reblock.  There
> should be a way to block while having another move selected.  Or better
> the individual move should automatically be reselected after each
> geniusmove.  It is unlikely that someone will want to do the same kind of
> move to the exact same set of men twice in a row.  In general, either you
> are going to select a new block or you are going to select another kind of
> move.

You're right.  I'll make it go back to individual move.

> I am still not convinced that smartmove is of much use.  But we've had
> this argument before.

I could add features that would make it better.  Like a smart move that
creates a circle or a curve instead of a line.

> There is no way (at least, not that I could find) to make arbitrarily
> named continuity groups.  This is important in many situations, such as
> dividing the band into two groups north and south of the 50.

Sure there is.  In the continuity editor, you pick "New continuity", or
something like that, from the menu.  To assign points to it, select the
points, select the continuity, and click on the button "Set points" (I
think.)

> So far I have only found two bugs.  Both of them caused the whole program
> to crash.  I've copied the error messages for you.
> 
> Closing the Setup Show window after setting number of points causes crash.
> 
> X Error:  BadPixmap
>   Request Major code 54 ()
>   ResourceID 0x2fb860
>   Error Serial #5696
>   Current Serial #5735
> 
> While reanimating, the program crashed.
> 
> X Error:  BadPixmap
>   Request Major code 54 ()
>   ResourceID 0x2ff960
>   Error Serial #76433
>   Current Serial #76461

After I added the MDI stuff, I tried to switch the X version back to the
old initial window and I got these.  But I went back and they went away.
It's most likely some incompatibility with the GUI library, but I'll check
it out.  The Windows version is probably okay.  Does this happen every
time?

