On Fri, 17 Oct 1997, Dan Isaksen wrote:

> Interestingly, the difference between the 2-point and the 3-point case can
> be determined internally without explicit direction from the user.  If all
> of the selected men lie on a line, then two moves will already uniquely
> determine where THAT LINE must go (even though it is not determined where
> other men must go, but that doesn't matter since no other men are
> selected).  Of course, the sources of the two moves must lie on the
> original line itself, but the destinations can be arbitrary.
> 
> This requires checking every time a block is selected whether all the men
> are collinear.  This is not bad algorithmically because the first two
> points determine a line and the rest just have to be checked.  So it's
> linear in the number of men selected.
> 
> Provided that the selected points are collinear, then geniusmove doesn't
> bother to wait for a third move, provided that the two sources lie on the
> line.  If the two sources do not lie on the line, the geniusmove waits for
> the third move, which will then determine everything in the usual way.

This sounds pretty good.  Actually, the collinear test should probably
happen after you make the second movement for genius move, not after every
selection.

However, I'm wondering if that covers all cases.  If you define p1->q1 and
p2->q2 you could define p3 and q3 such that (p3-p2) is a unit vector
orthogonal to (p1-p2) and likewise for q3.  Then the genius move is
defined and you can define many useful transformations (translation,
rotation, scaling in one dimension) with just two points (and for blocks
too, not just lines).  Is this right?

> > Some of the more technical parts I'll have to write, but the more general
> > stuff could be done by whoever has time first.
> 
