> However, I'm wondering if that covers all cases.  If you define p1->q1 and
> p2->q2 you could define p3 and q3 such that (p3-p2) is a unit vector
> orthogonal to (p1-p2) and likewise for q3.  Then the genius move is
> defined and you can define many useful transformations (translation,
> rotation, scaling in one dimension) with just two points (and for blocks
> too, not just lines).  Is this right?

Once you define p1 -> q1 and p2 -> q2, the destination of every point on
the line p1p2 is determined.  For example, the midpoint of p1p2 goes to
the midpoint of q1q2.  It doesn't matter what p3 and q3 are.  Of course,
p3 and q3 are important if you want to know the destinations of point not
on the line p1p2, but we don't care about that since all the selected
men lie on p1p2 in the first place.

> Well, I'll still be putting most of my time into the code because I think
> that's more urgent right now, but I think the first thing I should do is
> write a reference section of every menu item, toolbar item, button, etc.

Yes, I'd say that you should be putting all of your time spent on the
project into finishing the code.  When that is done, we can worry
more about the manual.

Dan



