On Sun, 19 Oct 1997, Dan Isaksen wrote:

> 
> > That sounds right.  I'm open to suggestions.  In particular, do you think
> > that there should be different colors for different directions?
> 
> Yes, but I think that the choices should perhaps be a bit more logical.
> White and yellow for east and west makes a lot of sense.  Perhaps two
> different shades of blue for north and south.  Red for collisions, orange
> for marked points.  I noticed that the points change color when they are
> performing continuity that the program had to generate because of
> mistakes; that's good.

Currently, collisions are purple (same color as the old version).  I was
thinking about some sort of symbol on top of the boxes to determine the
exact direction, maybe an arrow or a dot or something.  Then you could see
diagonal directions.  But as for the colors, I was really asking if
selected points should have different colors for different directions,
rather than just all orange.  That's how it is now, but the colors don't
make much sense.  But I suppose then I would have to have collisions be
different colors too.

> > > I think that the old-fashioned snap-to-grid feature is very useful.  Most
> > > of the time, you never want any points off the two-step block.
> > 
> > However, there is the side-effect that if you have one sheet with points
> > off the grid and you move it, it will mess up the formation.  But it's
> > probably the correct thing to do anyway.
> 
> Of course your worry is not a problem with individual move; it's just the
> multi-man moves that are a problem.  Rather than snapping points to grid
> locations, it is more important to snap the input data to grid locations.
> So you can turn a circle into an ellipse with a geniusmove, but you can't
> turn it into an arbitrary ellipse (since the geniusmove data points had to
> be on the grid).  Or you can rotate a line into funny angles, but not very
> very funny angles like 89.5 degrees.

Okay, I've this problem with rotations.  It still doesn't snap individual
points, but maybe I should at least have it clip the points onto the
field.  If they go off into never-never-land you can't get them back
except by undoing.  Maybe instead of snapping the points every time, you
can pick a menu option to snap the selected points onto the grid.

> > > I don't believe that having the program choose the order is going to be
> > > very useful.  Continuity considerations (e.g., avoiding collisions in
> > > pregame) HAVE to be considered.
> > 
> > I think you're talking the selection order feature now?  That's really a
> > different issue.  It would definately be useful to be able to move a line
> > into a nice curve, and smart move is probably the best way to do it.  The
> > selection order, on the other hand, allows smart move to be used with
> > random blocks.  Maybe it's useless, but it might be useful for changing
> > one curve into another.
> 
> You're right; we really are discussing two different issues.  Your
> observation about straight lines to curved lines would be very handy; this
> is how the commercial charting programs work.  They use some sort of
> spliny stuff to generate smooth curves from a few points.
> 
> However, smartmove as it is now either uses the arbitrary selection
> feature, or it is just a 2D geniusmove.  I think it is not useful in the
> first case; in the second case it is already covered by geniusmove. 

I agree.  I'm guessing that smart move won't be used as much now that
genius move is broken up.  At least WE wouldn't use it.  We'll have to see
what other people do.

Anyway, I did some more work over the weekend, but a machine was down so I
couldn't compile it for you.  Hopefully you can get it tomorrow.

-Rotations will snap to the grid.

-Shearing is implemented.

-Bug fixes (this was actually in a library, not my code.)  Hopefully this
will solve your crashes.  It occurs when not enough colors are available
(were you maybe running Netscape at the same time?) but it might have
manifested some other way.

-A couple other GUI changes.  The New and Open menu options open a new
window instead of changing the show in the current one (this makes the MDI
Windows interface more consistent.)  I also made the lassos and such a
different color.  And the default extension is .shw so you can open the
new shows.  Under Windows you can see both .shw and .mas files, but under
X you need to change the filter to "*.mas" to load an old show (you can
only see one and I think it's time for this.)

I'll let you know when you can get this.

Gurk



