> Sort of like harvey?  Man, that thing takes an eternity to compile
> calchart.  Anyway, calchart is fully functional.  I just finished all the

I would like to move off of harvey's current hardware in the somewhere
near future (i.e. 6-12 months).  When the next new computer is purchased
I'd like to move Harvey onto one of the old 486's with 16MB of RAM, and
probably trade it's 1GB SCSI HD for a 1.6 or 2.0 GB IDE HD from CalPerfs.

The RAM would be the same, and the processor would actually be a little
bit faster than the current one.  Slightly more importantly, it would
be easy to install a current version of BSDI/OS with security patches,
a full suite of software, etc.  Speed wouldn't be that much better,
but POP and IMAP would work as would Jove, Pine, Emacs, Pico, Kerberos,
etc., etc., etc.

And, maybe as important as the updated security patches (harvey now
is an open door waiting for any of 30 or 40 different security holes
to be exploited) is the fact that the hardware will be a few years 
newer and easily replaced or upgraded in the normal course of things--
if it died it could easily be replaced with another machine in a few
hours, and it can be upgraded every year when new machines are bought
and rotated through.

> genius move stuff.  I need to do a couple other things, like fix the

Whoopppieee!!!  Cool.  Congrats.

> scrolling and implement autosave.  About autosave, what did we decide was
> the correct Novell-friendly way to do it.  I remember that it's better to
> rename the last autosave, save the new one, then delete the old one.  What
> should the filename be?  I was thinking of saving it in the same directory
> with '#' in front (like emacs), but should it go into a separate
> directory?  And do you think 10 minutes is a good default?

It should go into the TEMP directory, set with the environment variable.
This is actually a somewhat important feature--if the network crashes
then the program can save the auto-save into the local disk if you 
just wait and let it...  It also cuts down on unnecessary network
bandwidth, etc.  Not to mention that it is the standard place to put
auto-save files unless the program has a separate configuration line
where you can specify where you want autosave files to go.

The filename should be anything that a user might not use.  Usually they
use an extension like .SAV or .ASV or .TMP or .~OC or .!OC (both of the
last two for DOC files, substitute the last two letters of the normal
file).

The rename, save, delete sequence is what should be done for normal data
files in Netware--it basically allows the Netware filesystem to re-allocate
the file based on it's new size efficiently as well as to save the work
of actually deleting the file for later (it's faster).  It also adds
data integrity on a moderately-used system--for instance, on the drive
that has a 3GB disk and is only 50% full the system still has all of
the deleted files from the last 2 months sitting around just in case
they should want to be recovered.  It's really nice when someone has 
a problem to be able to go in an give them 50 different time stamps
of when they can recover the file from.

> Actually, I still need to do something to enter the continuity that get
> printed, but I can add a temporary solution if that isn't done in time for
> spring show.

I'd say entering continuity is a slightly important feature... :-)

> It only took me three years (if you count the early printing program...
> two for the rest of the program).  Now we'll see if it passes Dan's tests
> (I already had to fix a bunch of bugs when I tried it on shows from '90
> using commands only Dan would think to use.)
> 
> Gurk

Rune


