> very close to directly above (or below) p1.  Or exact 60 degree rotations
> are also easy; select p2 to be near the point that is 2 north and 4 west
> of p1.  No snapping of individual points is required or even desirable.

The communication problem is that I meant to write "I've FIXED this
problem with rotations..."  It has the behavior you've mentioned.  I was
wondering if you might ever want each point individually snapped, but this
should probably be a separate step.  But I think they should be clipped
onto the field (if you do a smart move with too many points for instance).

> > I agree.  I'm guessing that smart move won't be used as much now that
> > genius move is broken up.  At least WE wouldn't use it.  We'll have to see
> > what other people do.
> 
> But don't you believe that the old-fashioned geniusmove is useful?  We
> have no feature that performs that function.

What?  It's the last button of the transforms on the toolbar.  It
functions like the original except there's no special case for when the
points are collinear (I'll take a look at how the old version handles it.)

> > -Bug fixes (this was actually in a library, not my code.)  Hopefully this
> > will solve your crashes.  It occurs when not enough colors are available
> > (were you maybe running Netscape at the same time?) but it might have
> > manifested some other way.
> 
> Yes, I was running netscape, come to think of it.  I will give it a try
> without netscape.

You could also run 'netscape -install' to use it's own colormap or
'netscape -ncols 128' to only use 128 colors.  Either one will make more
available to other programs.

>  
> > -A couple other GUI changes.  The New and Open menu options open a new
> > window instead of changing the show in the current one (this makes the MDI
> > Windows interface more consistent.)  I also made the lassos and such a
> > different color.  And the default extension is .shw so you can open the
> > new shows.  Under Windows you can see both .shw and .mas files, but under
> > X you need to change the filter to "*.mas" to load an old show (you can
> > only see one and I think it's time for this.)
> 
> I'm not working at all on loading and saving.  In the past I have had
> a lot of trouble getting that to work on my platform.  I guess loading and
> saving are more platform-dependent than most functions.

I recall you tried to load a show from '90 and it didn't work (it was an
even older format, but it's now supported.)  But a lot of the old shows
are corrupted or have continuity that should be illegal, so I don't care
too much about compatibility.

The new version has its own file format (the .shw files), and I'd like to
know if you have any problems with this.  And yes, it is more
platform-dependent because different machines store numbers differently in
memory and it works the same internally, but if you save that number to
disk and then read it on another machine you'll have garbage if you don't
convert it.  This should be taken care of... I'd like to know of any
problems you have.  Actually, I've been doing all my testing on an Intel
machine, which is different from a Sun, so if you create a big show, I'd
like you to mail it to me so I can test it.  Or you could get an old show
(say from '95) save it in the new format, see if you can load and animate
the new file, and then send it to me.

Gurk



