[...]
> I was thinking of making it configurable if it didn't go in the same
> directory. I guess the default would be TMPDIR under UNIX and TEMP under
> Windows.  I was thinking that you would want to use Netware to get older
> versions of the autosave file, but maybe that's not important.  Do Windows

It's a tradeoff--having more copies of the autosave file available vs.
having someplace to save if the network connection is lost.

> programs usually detect a newer autosave file?  I'm thinking of the Emacs
> feature where it asks you if you want to use the autosave file instead.

Most Windows programs do--they detect an autosave file either when
you open the program for the first time (these usually keep the
autosave file in a particular directory) or when you try to open the
data file (these usually keep the autosave file in the same place
as the data file).

> > The filename should be anything that a user might not use.  Usually they
> > use an extension like .SAV or .ASV or .TMP or .~OC or .!OC (both of the
> > last two for DOC files, substitute the last two letters of the normal
> > file).
> 
> I'm using the extension .SHW for the new calchart files.  I'll probably
> use .SAV for autosave files (I'd like to save .~HW or .!HW under UNIX.)

Why not use .~HW or .!HW for Windows too?

> > The rename, save, delete sequence is what should be done for normal data
> > files in Netware--it basically allows the Netware filesystem to re-allocate
> > the file based on it's new size efficiently as well as to save the work
> > of actually deleting the file for later (it's faster).  It also adds
> > data integrity on a moderately-used system--for instance, on the drive
> > that has a 3GB disk and is only 50% full the system still has all of
> > the deleted files from the last 2 months sitting around just in case
> > they should want to be recovered.  It's really nice when someone has 
> > a problem to be able to go in an give them 50 different time stamps
> > of when they can recover the file from.
> 
> Come to think of it, I'm currently just overwriting the file when you
> save.  But doesn't the rename, save, delete sequence have the problem of
> losing all the file attributes?  There are probably Novell calls to do
> this, but I'd rather not include Novell code.

OK.  So what they actually do I suppose is copy the file to a temp
file, modify the original, then delete the temp file.  There aren't
usually any file permissions, though--DOS only allows Read-Only (which
obviously isn't set if you're changing it or renaming it), System
(which programs aren't supposed to use), Hidden (which programs aren't
supposed to use) and Archive (which gets set automatically when the
file is modified anyway).  Netware doesn't normally add any really either
that affect data files except maybe the "Transactional" flag, but none
of these would be that.  But maybe Copy A -> ~A, Modify A, Delete ~A
is the better way to go.  Most Netware permissions and such are 
given in the directory, not the individual file.

[...]
> Gurk

Rune

