You don't need to make a big show.  Just save a recent show and send it to
me.  The shows from '90 to '95 are on the web page.

Some pointless computer trivia... remember how I was saying that different
computers store numbers differently?  The common difference is the order
of bytes.  So for a 32-bit integer, you have four 8-bit number (A, B, C,
D) so the number is A*2^24 + B*2^16 + C*2^8 + D.  Sometimes the number is
stored in memory in the order ABCD and sometimes it's DCBA.  ABCD is
called big-endian (many workstations) and DCBA is little-endian (Intel
machines).  Some processors can be switched.  Internally it works the
same, but you can't just save the memory to disk if you want it to be
portable. The names big-endian and little-endian come from Gulliver's
Travels because there were two cities that couldn't agree on whether to
open an egg from the big or little end.

Gurk



