> transformation and drag a peak into a line.  If you have a ref point p0,
> you start dragging at p1, and end at p2, the scale factor for y is
> (p2y-p0y)/(p1y-p0y) which is 0.  So the matrix would be (ignoring
> translation components):
> 
> | 1 0 0 |
> | 0 0 0 |
> | 0 0 0 |
> 
> Which you definately couldn't do with regular genius move.  Right?

This can be done with geniusmove.  The affine transformation is simply
projection onto a line.  I think your confusion arises from the fact that
this map is not invertible, but affine transformations (in our sense, at
least) don't have to be invertible.  

I edited your picture slightly.  Send x to x, send y to y, and send z to
w.  Then the geniusmove sends all the points straight down onto the line
passing through x and y.

The problem with chevrons arises when they are stacked the other way (see
below).  It is not possible to turn this figure into a series of vertical
lines with geniusmove.

*   *   *
 *   *   *
  *   *   *
   *   *   *
  *   *   *
 *   *   *
*   *   *

> As for the animation colors, I couldn't get a scheme I like.  You can edit
> runtime/config yourself to experiment.  The lines to edit should be
> obvious.  You can change the color names to three integers (0-255 for the
> red, green, and blue components).  The values for the normal ones are
> something like:  

I have no intuition for color components because I rarely work with them,
so I don't think I'm going to have any more luck than you have had.
 
Dan



