I have only just begun, but here are some ideas that I have had so far.


As I go along, I am keeping track of which features are used so
repetitively that a keyboard shortcut is very important.  So far, they are
Set Title, Set Beats, Insert Sheet, and Reanimate.


Right now, all caps is required in the continuity editor.  Perhaps we
should switch everything to all lowercase for ease of typing.


GV is not a defined constant.  It should be 1.  This was added after the
manual was written, so it is not in there. 


DIR(P) should give an error or something.  Right now it defaults to N.


DOF is always N, no matter what direction I just moved.


If you negate the second parameter of a procedure where the first
parameter is also numerical, then the parser misinterprets these two
parameters as a single parameter.  If you put parentheses around the
second parameter, then it works fine.  I'm not sure that this is a bug;
just a design quirk.  For example,

    MARCH HS -8 S

is interpreted as

    MARCH -7 270 

and then dies because there is no third parameter.


The order of operations is now algebraic, not left-to-right as in the old
version.  Again, not a bug, but change the (online) manual.


I think that it would be handy to have a new point variable called SP.  It
is the starting position on a sheet.  There have been times in the past
when I have had to use "dummy" reference points to refer to this location,
but that is a bogus way of doing it.


Is it worthwhile installing some looping and forking possibilities in the
continuity language?  Possibly, but no one would use them but you and me,
and neither of us are in the band anymore!


I have been following Chapter 6 of the manual for ideas on exactly what to
test.  It has been very useful.  Going back over it now, I am astounded at
how thorough we were.  Unreadable it is, but it is also complete.

The manual says, "If a reference point is not defined in the stuntsheet
editor, then it defaults to the initial location of P on the stuntsheet."
This sentence was written when we didn't think about reference points in
the same way that we do now.  Nowadays, reference points are ALWAYS
defined.  The point of this sentence is that the default location for
reference points is SP.  So change the (online) manual.

More to come.

Dan



