On Wed, 22 Oct 1997, Dan Isaksen wrote:

> 
> I have only just begun, but here are some ideas that I have had so far.
> 
> 
> As I go along, I am keeping track of which features are used so
> repetitively that a keyboard shortcut is very important.  So far, they are
> Set Title, Set Beats, Insert Sheet, and Reanimate.

The menus have short-cuts in Windows, but they don't work in Motif.  In
Windows, it'll be several keys, like Alt E (for Edit) T is the sequence
for Set Title.  I can (should) add single key shortcuts for many things
(like the toolbar buttons).

> Right now, all caps is required in the continuity editor.  Perhaps we
> should switch everything to all lowercase for ease of typing.

Yeah, I believe it is case-sensitive.  Should I make case-insensitive (so
MARCH = March = march = maRcH)?  I don't see any problems from this.

> GV is not a defined constant.  It should be 1.  This was added after the
> manual was written, so it is not in there. 

What is the meaning of this constant?

> DIR(P) should give an error or something.  Right now it defaults to N.

I believe the manual says it will default to N, but I'll change that.
Backwards compatibility isn't that important.

> DOF is always N, no matter what direction I just moved.

I'll look into it.

> If you negate the second parameter of a procedure where the first
> parameter is also numerical, then the parser misinterprets these two
> parameters as a single parameter.  If you put parentheses around the
> second parameter, then it works fine.  I'm not sure that this is a bug;
> just a design quirk.  For example,
> 
>     MARCH HS -8 S
> 
> is interpreted as
> 
>     MARCH -7 270 
> 
> and then dies because there is no third parameter.

Most modern parsers want to reduce expressions immediately.  This is a
problem with a language like this where expressions are ambiguous with
multiple values unless you look at the number of values.  Usually a comma
is required to separate multiple values.  I could probably rewrite the
grammar to look at spaces...  1-8 would mean -7 but 1 -8 would always be
two value if they aren't enclosed in parenthesis.  The other alternative
is to make parenthesis required when you want to do subtration.  Or I
could introduce optional commas that clear this up.  I could write a more
intelligent parser, but I don't know if that's worth it.  What do you
think?

> The order of operations is now algebraic, not left-to-right as in the old
> version.  Again, not a bug, but change the (online) manual.

I didn't realize I changed it.  That's good don't you think?  (Ignore
comptibility.)

> I think that it would be handy to have a new point variable called SP.  It
> is the starting position on a sheet.  There have been times in the past
> when I have had to use "dummy" reference points to refer to this location,
> but that is a bogus way of doing it.

Easy enough...

> Is it worthwhile installing some looping and forking possibilities in the
> continuity language?  Possibly, but no one would use them but you and me,
> and neither of us are in the band anymore!

I can see that an if/else command might be useful.  Maybe the looping so
you can say, execute these commands ten times.  The continuity would start
to look like code.  This wouldn't be that hard, so I'll keep it in mind.

> I have been following Chapter 6 of the manual for ideas on exactly what to
> test.  It has been very useful.  Going back over it now, I am astounded at
> how thorough we were.  Unreadable it is, but it is also complete.

And how necessary it is.  I couldn't imagine not having access to it.

> The manual says, "If a reference point is not defined in the stuntsheet
> editor, then it defaults to the initial location of P on the stuntsheet."
> This sentence was written when we didn't think about reference points in
> the same way that we do now.  Nowadays, reference points are ALWAYS
> defined.  The point of this sentence is that the default location for
> reference points is SP.  So change the (online) manual.

I'll update that.  I think I asked you this before, but should NP be
defined on the last sheet.  I think it's currently defined as P.
Obviously the end point can't be known if you're depending on NP.

So the other additions are direction to face for the MARCH command and
step size for the FOUNTAIN command.  I'm planning on making a variable
number of arguments to these commands (so omitting the new argument will
have the effect of the old command).

Are you looking at the HTML version of the manual?  The online help
program for X is sort of lame.  There's a new version that uses HTML files
so it should look better, but I haven't tried it.  I can build it for you
if you want.  You can get to the top level from the main window, or you
can go straight to the animation commands from the continuity editor.

Also, continuity errors report the line number, but the continuity editors
don't display them.  I was thinking of having the cursors automatically
positioned to the error, but haven't gotten to it.

Gurk



