X-Status: A


> Yeah, I believe it is case-sensitive.  Should I make case-insensitive (so
> MARCH = March = march = maRcH)?  I don't see any problems from this.

I think that case-insensitivity is the way to go.
 
> > GV is not a defined constant.  It should be 1.  This was added after the
> > manual was written, so it is not in there. 
> 
> What is the meaning of this constant?

Grapevine.  Come to think of it, maybe GV was a procedure, not a stepsize.
Regardless, GV should be a stepsize, and GRAPEVINE can be a procedure if
you want to install it.
 
> > DIR(P) should give an error or something.  Right now it defaults to N.
> 
> I believe the manual says it will default to N, but I'll change that.
> Backwards compatibility isn't that important.

Come to think of it, there are times when you want to use DIR(x) where x
is the current position.  For example, if some men have already reached
their destination and you execute

   MARCH HS DIST(NP) DIR(NP)

most men will march to their next position, and the ones already there
won't do anything.

The correct mathematical solution is to define DIR(P) to be some
non-numerical value, say infinity.  Then

   MARCH HS D infinity

means nothing if D = 0 but gives an error if D is not zero.  Similar
special cases would have to be installed in other procedures as well.

DOF should also be infinity at the beginning of a stuntsheet before any
direction of flow has been specified.

Is this a completely unrealistic suggestion from the point of view of a
programmer?
 
> Most modern parsers want to reduce expressions immediately.  This is a
> problem with a language like this where expressions are ambiguous with
> multiple values unless you look at the number of values.  Usually a comma
> is required to separate multiple values.  I could probably rewrite the
> grammar to look at spaces...  1-8 would mean -7 but 1 -8 would always be
> two value if they aren't enclosed in parenthesis.  The other alternative
> is to make parenthesis required when you want to do subtration.  Or I
> could introduce optional commas that clear this up.  I could write a more
> intelligent parser, but I don't know if that's worth it.  What do you
> think?

I think it doesn't matter very much.  How often do users input negative
numbers for procedure arguments?  Almost never.  If you're smart enough to
use negation (i.e., if you're not on Stunt), then you're probably smart
enough to use parentheses.
 
> > The order of operations is now algebraic, not left-to-right as in the old
> > version.  Again, not a bug, but change the (online) manual.
> 
> I didn't realize I changed it.  That's good don't you think?  (Ignore
> comptibility.)

Definitely.  The reason for left-to-right was Martin's laziness.
 
> > I have been following Chapter 6 of the manual for ideas on exactly what to
> > test.  It has been very useful.  Going back over it now, I am astounded at
> > how thorough we were.  Unreadable it is, but it is also complete.
> 
> And how necessary it is.  I couldn't imagine not having access to it.

I know what you mean.  It would be hopeless trying to test these specific
features without a written description of what they are supposed to do.  I
would never be able to remember all the aspects.
 
> I'll update that.  I think I asked you this before, but should NP be
> defined on the last sheet.  I think it's currently defined as P.
> Obviously the end point can't be known if you're depending on NP.

It seems to me that NP should be undefined on the last sheet, especially
since SP now exists.  Only a Stunt member would type

  FMTO NP

on the last sheet.
 
> Are you looking at the HTML version of the manual?  The online help
> program for X is sort of lame.  There's a new version that uses HTML files
> so it should look better, but I haven't tried it.  I can build it for you
> if you want.  You can get to the top level from the main window, or you
> can go straight to the animation commands from the continuity editor.

I am using a hard copy that you sent me a year or two ago.  The online
help has never worked (remember the timing out dialog box infinite loop?).
Are the HTML files on the Calchart web page?
 
Dan

