> I think the easier way to do it is to only evaluate the expression if it
> needs to.  This would have the same result in most cases, but it wouldn't
> catch errors (expression errors, not parse errors) like MARCH HS 0 (45/0).
> However, it's possible to do it your way.  There are special values
> defined for infinity, negative infinity, and NaN (not a number, which you
> get if you try to take the square root of -1 for instance).

What I am trying to do is prevent a command like

  MARCH HS 8 DIR(P)

to have the same effect as

  MARCH HS 8 N, 

while allowing a command like

  MARCH HS DIST(NP) DIR(NP)

to not give an error message when P = NP.  [Theoretical computer
scientists might get a laugh out of the previous sentence.]

Here is one problem with your solution.  The command

  MARCH HS DIR(P) N

should return an error, but your suggestion would cause it to execute the
null procedure errorlessly.  Admittedly, non-Stunt people are unlikely to
ever type such a command.  

I believe that the only way to catch all of the difficulties at once is
by assigning DIR(P) to be NaN.

> As for DOF, it turned out that I just forgot to handle this.  Can this
> just defined as the current direction once a mark time or movement has
> been given?  I guess maybe you want to avoid something like MARCH HS 8 DOF
> as the first command, but after that it should be legal.  I guess
> something like MAGIC should make it undefined again.

Perhaps DOF should be equal to the last direction from the previous
stuntsheet, but maybe that will be hard to code.  At the beginning of the
first stuntsheet, DOF should equal NaN.  I suppose that you are right
about MAGIC.  However, I worry that we are being so anal about the
"logical correctness" that we are hurting usage.  Does anyone ever need to
know the direction of the previous flow after a MAGIC?  Yes, if you just
used MAGIC to snap to grid.
 
> The docs are on the web page in HTML, postscript, LaTeX, and RTF (which
> you load into Word).  I also have the docs for TeX2RTF, which is the
> program used to convert the LaTeX docs to all the other formats.  I can
> give you this program for Sun if you need it when writing the manual.  You
> might want to look at the TeX2RTF docs because not all LaTeX commands are
> supported.

I am much happier with a hard copy of the manual because it is quicker to
turn pages and so forth.

When writing the manual, we have two choices as to the format of what I
write.  One is plain text that you can format later in whatever form you
wish.  The other choice is Latex, so we'll probably need TeX2RTF
eventually.  But I could just send you the files, and you could deal with
it.  That will probably be technically easier than trying to install it
here.
 
> As for the online help, I was having this problem too on Linux, but when I
> rebuilt my system it went again.  Maybe it's worth trying again if I think
> you would use it.

The only reason that you should try to get the online help to work is if
you want me to test it.


Here are some ideas I have had for organization of the manual.

Foreword - history.

Overview - motivation for new version; organization of manual.

Getting Started - the small main window; how to start and quit; maybe the
bare minimum like how to set the number of men, how to individual move,
how to create a new stuntsheet.  

[Up until this point, the text should be in a tutorial format, but after
this point it should be a reference manual.]

Show Setup - all about the setup window.

Files - saving; loading; file formats.

Stuntsheet Editor - all about the stuntsheet editing window (probably the
longest chapter).

Continuity Editor - all about the continuity editing window, including the
description of the continuity language.

Animator - all about the animation window.

Printing - all about printing, including continuity printing.

Multiple Shows - how to use several windows to look at different shows;
merging.

Technical Stuff - whatever you need to put in here about installing the
program, hardware required, or whatever.

Index



You will have to write the Files and Technical chapters because I don't
know about that stuff.  Also, I know very little about the printing, so
you should probably write that, too.  However, I could do most of the
rest.

I was thinking of just copying Martin's historical notes (and crediting
him for the text, of course) from the 2.0 manual and then adding some more
about what has happenned since then. 

Dan



From gmeeker@lucasdigital.com Fri Oct 24 13:19:47 1997
