I've been busy, but I've done a little more.  I've added SP and GV, and
hopefully fixed division by zero, undefined values like NP, DIR(P), and
implemented DOF (but probably doesn't do the correct thing after MAGIC).
This is on the web page (actually the DOF changes aren't there yet because
harvey was down last night.)  It's still case sensitive though.

On Fri, 24 Oct 1997, Dan Isaksen wrote:

> 
> If you install if/else capability in the continuity language, then the
> expression "P = NP" would appear occasionally.
> 
> Subroutines would be a handy thing.  One could request the execution of
> another groups continuity.  This is useful when there are four types of
> men: plain, solid, slash, and solidslash; the plains and solids start out
> doing the same thing while the slashes and solidslashes are also doing the
> same thing.  But in the second half of the flow, the plains and slashes
> are together while the solids and solidslashes are together.  This
> situations has arisen many times for me.  Use of subroutines is the
> natural solution.

In order to do this, you would need to define subroutines on a per
stuntsheet basic, rather than a per continuity group basis like everything
else.

> As I test the language, I create a show with only 1 point.  The program
> asks me how many men to put in each column.  The default value is 10,
> which is kind of silly when there is only 1 new point.  If the number of
> new points is less than 10, then the default should be equal to the number
> of new points.

I don't think this will usually come up, but I'll change that.

> In the old program, I hated having to scroll to the east or west edges of
> the field to make sure that I was on the correct yardline.  The
> yardmarkers should always be visible at either the bottom or the top of
> the screen, no matter where you are on the field.

I'll try to do this when I change the scrolling method.  I'm picturing a
separate scrolling "ruler" below or above the field.

> The color of the line in individual mode does not contrast enough with the
> white field lines.  It should really stand out; it is almost impossible to
> see what you are doing when you move due east/west along a yardline.

I'll fix all the colors soon.  I just wanted to change it from white, but
grey was a bad choice.

> There should be a way to reset all the reference points to coincide with
> the actual positions of the men.

I thought I did that.  I'll have to check tonight.

> Should there be a command for "FMTO NP; MRTM W"?  There probably should be
> a command because it is used so often.  But what could it be called?  By
> the way, I believe that this should be the default continuity if no
> instructions are given or if there is "Not enough to do".

The default right now is EVEN NP or MTRM W if it's the last sheet.  I
think you're probably right.  Maybe something like FMMT NP W?

> Division by zero gives an empty error message, not a "Division by zero"
> error message.

Fixed.

> The first thing I always do is zoom to 10.  Is this an artifact of the
> pixel size on the machines I use?  I looked through the config file, but I
> didn't see any way to reset the default.

I guess I made 5 the default because the band's computers were like
640x480, but this should set in the config file.

> I wonder why Martin only allowed A, B, C, D, X, Y, and Z to be variables.
> I'm certainly not complaining.  I recall using variables once or twice.
> It just seems so arbitrary.  Probably he only allowed those because E and
> W already have meanings.

We could use something like $whatever to denote a variable, but I don't
think it matters much.

> I'd like to be able to view several reference points at once, even if I
> can only move one group at a time.  It especially helps in setting up
> countermarches.

I've also thought about viewing other sheets the same way as reference
points.

> The main small window keeps popping up into the foreground every time
> there is a dialog box.  I like to have it iconified because I almost never
> use it and it just gets in the way.

Hmmm, probably because the dialogs are parented to the main window.  I'll
check it out.  The interface is sort of geared towards Windows, so it
doesn't quite look right under X.  I'd like to get rid of the main window,
but the library I'm using doesn't allow that.

> If you give COUNTERMARCH a negative number of steps, it pivots before it
> ever reaches the point where the countermarch starts.  I'm not saying
> that's wrong.  I just wonder whether the correct procedure would be for it
> to march to the starting point, then backtrack, then pivot.  Obviously it
> doesn't matter too much, but we might as well do it right.  The reason it
> does one or the other is an artifact of the way the countermarch is
> calculated.
> 
> If you give COUNTERMARCH a negative number of beats, it completely ignores
> the command (although it doesn't give an error).  Should it do the
> countermarch in reverse?  I think that is correct.

Probably.  I wasn't really thinking about negative numbers.

> Are all commands going to be reversible like that with a negative number
> of beats (or negative stepsize)?  Let's look through the list, since it's
> right in front of me.  
> 
> EVEN: a possibility is MARCH DIST(<destination>/(-<steps>)
>       -<steps> OPP(DIR(<destination>).  But why would you want to march
>       directly away from your destination until you exactly double your 
>       distance to the destination?  
> FM: just reverse the direction.
> HSCM: reverse the direction of countermarch
> MARCH: reverse the direction (this is already installed).
> MT: a possibility is to just take the absolute value here.  This is
>     consistent with the fact that MT <steps> <direction> is the same
>     as MARCH 0 <steps> <direction>.
> ROTATE: reverse the direction of rotation.

I think that some places just cast the number of steps to a natural
integer.  I'd also appreciate any thoughts on what to do with
non-integers.

> After testing MARCH thoroughly and working through the introductory
