> > Perhaps DOF should be equal to the last direction from the previous
> > stuntsheet, but maybe that will be hard to code.  At the beginning of the
> > first stuntsheet, DOF should equal NaN.  I suppose that you are right
> > about MAGIC.  However, I worry that we are being so anal about the
> > "logical correctness" that we are hurting usage.  Does anyone ever need to
> > know the direction of the previous flow after a MAGIC?  Yes, if you just
> > used MAGIC to snap to grid.
> 
> The easiest thing would be to make it the direction a point is currently
> facing (or NaN at the very beginning).  But what about ROTATE?  What
> should DOF be set to then?  It wouldn't be much harder to make DOF be the
> direction from the end of the last stuntsheet, but I'm not sure that's the
> correct thing.  What if you're executing several commands?  Do you really
> want it to still be defined from the last stuntsheet?

I meant that DOF should be equal to the last direction from the previous
stuntsheet on the first beat of each sheet.  I think that "current
direction" is the correct idea to keep in mind when deciding conventions
on DOF.  So during ROTATE, DOF is equal to the tangent at P to the obvious
circle.  I think that it is correct that MAGIC and GRID cause DOF to be
NaN.
 
