	id xma026125; Sun, 14 Dec 97 13:07:02 -0800
Received: from zarquon.uchicago.edu (zarquon.uchicago.edu [128.135.72.16]) by harvey.calband.berkeley.edu (8.6.12/8.6.12) with ESMTP id NAA10757 for <gurk@calband.berkeley.edu>; Sun, 14 Dec 1997 13:01:40 -0800
Received: (from dci@localhost)
	by zarquon.uchicago.edu (8.8.7-s-4/8.8.7) id PAA26355;
	Sun, 14 Dec 1997 15:01:41 -0600 (CST)
From: Dan Isaksen <dci@math.uchicago.edu>
Message-Id: <199712142101.PAA26355@zarquon.uchicago.edu>
To: gurk@CalBand.Berkeley.EDU
Date: Sun, 14 Dec 1997 15:01:39 -0600 (CST)
Cc: dci@zarquon.uchicago.edu (Dan Isaksen)
X-Mailer: ELM [version 2.4 PL25]
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=US-ASCII
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Length: 6391
Status: RO
X-Status: A


Recall several days ago I asked Rune to tell us about the recent CBAA
meeting.  He never responded, so I'll tell what little I heard from Dick.

The alumni welcomed the new ExComm in the usual way by complaining about a
bunch of stuff and living up to students' expectations of annoying alumni.
One of the things they complained about was that the charting has become
terrible over the last few years.  It's all the same stuff - geometric
step-two drills.  The blame for this was put on CalChart.  All of the
charting complainers were from before 1980, with one notable exception;
Greg Jones was one of the ringleaders.  He recalled that he agreed to the
original project with the warning that if it ever became a crutch to
charters, he would immediately delete the program from the computers.  He
feels like going into the office right now and deleting it.

I definitely believe that this issue is something that we should consider
seriously.  I have a bunch of observations to make, in no particular
order.  I am writing this to you mostly for my own sake so that I can
organize my thoughts on the issue.  Also, it is something that we should
deal with in program design and manual writing.  Is there anyone else who
would be interested in this discussion?



There is no question that the charting has changed over the last few
years, and I have no doubt that CalChart has had some effect.  I recall an
email to the alumni list a few years ago (I think it was from Stretch)
after he saw a halftime show for the first time in a few years.  He was
impressed with the dramatically increased intricacy and technical
complications of the charting.  Not everyone thinks the change is such a
disaster. 



The program was originally written for a different purpose than it is now
used.  We got handwritten shows from the charters, and then we put all the
data in the computer, checked for collisions, and printed it out.
The reason we created geniusmove was that it took us less than half the
time to process a show.  Out of a 30 sheet show, about 3 sheets could not
be handled with geniusmove.  Now geniusmove is used as a device for making
up new formations, a purpose for which it was not intended and not
necessarily suitable.  There are some relevant lines from the introduction
of the 2.0 manual by Martin.  "CalChart is _not_ good for starting a show
from scratch.... Shows designed this way often lack aesthetic quality,
because the designer did not try to visualize the flows in their head.
CalChart is no good for doodling.... It is easier and faster when
conceiving a show to sketch out ideas on paper than to do all the work on
the computer."  Of course, this idea was never accepted by the users.
When you have a fancy program available for use, it is only natural to use
it and avoid pencil-and-paper methods.  I feel somewhat guilty for
allowing this attitude to persist because it was under my term as Adm-Poop
that these traditions were established.  If I had resisted more, maybe it
would have made a difference.  This is doubtful; as soon I left, it would
have happenned anyway.



The advent of CalChart is not the only possible cause of the change.  Here
are some other possible causes. 

1) Maybe change is always occurring, whether we use computer programs or
not.  Perhaps this is not really a recent phenomenon.

2) Tony Martinez charted every single show until the mid80s.

3) When I was a newman, two of the regular season shows were charted by
paid professionals (former bandsmen).  When I was a senior, all of the
regular season shows were charted by current students.  Has this
deprofessionalization continued in the past few years?  I don't have any
facts on that.  Imagine what would happen to the quality of music if MAC
started writing all the arrangements.



The idea of deleting the program is not a serious option.  Technology
itself is not evil; it's what you do with it that can be bad.  The
solution (if there even is a problem) is to use the program appropriately. 



There are some things that CalChart has done wonderfully.  Pregame
rehearsals used to be a nightmare; collisions arose that Stunt didn't know
about until people bumped into each other at rehearsal.  They had to
rechart on the fly.  This reason alone completely justifies Calchart's
existence.

Even for halftime shows, collision checking has been a big help.  I stayed
in Berkeley for Christmas before the Citrus Bowl.  Sam Arucan had charted
the halftime show on paper, and I processed it for him.  One of his famous
escalator flows was full of collisions.  He tried several times to fix it
up, but each time there were problems.  Finally, he found a solution.  We
spent hours working back and forth trying to fix it.  This could never
have been done between rehearsals in Orlando.  The flow would have been
scrapped for something boring.

Stuntsheet printing is also a huge advantage.  There used to be all kinds
of problems with people not being able to read the labels on the
handwritten sheets.  The process of making the sheets took many hours of
labor, not to mention the expense of refreshments for the poopers.



The important question is not what happenned and why, but what we can do
with version 3 to solve some of these problems.  Is there even a problem
to be solved?  I am inclined to doubt the severity of the situation. 
Current bandsmen aren't complaining, and that's what is important to me.
It is appropriate for alumni to observe to current bandsmen that a change
has taken place (because current bandsmen don't have a historical
perspective), but it is inappropriate for alumni to demand specific
actions.  If the bandsmen don't want to do it, then that's fine.

I feel it is important that the current StuntComm understand what we are
doing and approve of our project.  I don't want to present them with a
finished package that they don't want.  I realize that it is hard to get
feedback from them.  I think the only way that we're going to get feedback
is when they start using version 3 fulltime after you install a "finished"
version on their computers.  We should expect to go back and make a lot of
changes after the first season of use, following Stunt's recommendations.

Also, we should write about the potential hazards of CalChart in a
prominent way in the manual.  Not that anyone will ever read it anyway,
but there's the principle of it.



Dan


