I agree with you on pretty much everything.  I don't think calchart is
evil.  There has been some interesting charting done by some people with
calchart.  I can think of Neil (who charted the Earth Wind and Fire show
that Stretch commented on), Sang, and Trevor, who all put out good shows
done with calchart.  The problem that I've noticed is that charters are
now able to use scatter-like flows when they're stuck.  Before they would
have had to think things through more.  I think they're also relying more
on calchart to visualize the show, instead of visualizing it in their
heads.  Adding a 3D view may help this, since viewing an overhead view of
a bunch of dots can be quite different than the actual show, especially
from where most people sit.  It shouldn't be difficult to add this
feature, but of course I need to finish the important stuff first.

Of course, there are people that take this too far.  I recall Dan Pearson
saying that pregame looked so much better before calchart because there
were flows.  And the new drum major and some people applying for stunt
seem very excited about the new calchart, although I think that's largely
due to limitations of the current version.

Also, Mac does sometimes arrange shows (or students anyways).  Chris
Berry, Cory Cook, and the current StuD have done arrangements for shows.
Or gotten a professional arrangement and decided to re-arrange part of it.
But I agree that your observation about professional charting is as
important as the observation that calchart has changed charting.

It's interesting that you are now in favor of preaching in the manual
about how to chart.  You seemed against the idea earlier.

As for other features to improve charting, I don't have any ideas, but the
3D thing could be big.  I think the fact that you can experiment more
without destroying your show is important.  I can recall times when I had
to make a copy of a show before I tried something new, and I don't think
most stunt members know how to do that.

Gurk

