At least in the UNIX version, temporary files don't have unique names.  I
can't actually produce an error, but I'm sure you could screw things up by
running the program twice simultaneously and editing the same show in
each.  Of course, it is not necessary to run two copies of the program
simultaneously because you can open more windows with just one copy.
Maybe there should be a lock against running the program twice at the same
time.

Was there a reason that blockmove is started with shift, rather than with
clicking on an icon?  It seems more consistent as an icon.  Maybe I was
worried that blockmoves are so frequent that an icon would get tiresome.
I am less concerned by that now because I have seen firsthand that the
icons are pretty easy to use.  Even if we leave shift as the blockmove
starter, there should also be an icon.

What about nomenclature for the Geniusmoves?  This will be necessary for
the manual.  I think that Reflectionmove, Rotationmove, Dilationmove, and
Shearmove are clearly the best choices.  We need a term for the
old-fashioned Geniusmove, and we need another term for all five kinds.
Perhaps Geniusmove for the generic name, and Affinemove for the
old-fashioned.  This is consistent with the other four names because the
specific names are all geometric.

When choosing the angle with Rotationmove, sometimes the longer of the two
possible arcs is shown.  I can't get it to show the longer arc right now,
but I was definitely doing it earlier.  The shorter arc should always be
shown.

In Shearmove, the line doesn't have to be perpendicular to the direction
to the origin.  It can run in any direction, as long as it doesn't contain
the origin.

Reflectionmove will almost never be used unless the reflection line is
running in one of the 8 cardinal directions.  It is so unlikely to use a
non-standard reflection that I am inclined to disable arbitrary lines and
restrict the freedom only to the 8 cardinal directions.  But I guess there
is no loss of functionality by allowing arbitrary reflection lines.

In Dilationmove, the line should always contain the origin.  The way it
works now, the line is projected into such a line before the Dilationmove
acts. 

In Affinemove, a zero translation should be indicated with an X or
something.  Right now it doesn't show up on the screen at all, even though
it has been entered.  This is important because a zero translation is a
very common kind of input for a Affinemove, although it may become less
common now that we have the other kinds of Geniusmoves.

In what order should the icons be?  I think that Rotationmove will be used
least commonly.  Dilationmove and Shearmove will probably be most common,
and Reflectionmove and Affinemove somewhere in the middle.

I have not yet checked all the degenerate cases for the Geniusmoves.

I undid a lot of stuff today because I was making lots of stuntsheet
edits, and it worked fine.  I redid everything, and that worked fine also. 

Dan






