At some point, the Reflectionmove icon was highlighted incorrectly.  It
stayed highlighted even during selecting other Geniusmoves, until I
selected Reflectionmove and then selected another icon.  I can't reproduce
it, but I know it happenned.

We should distinguish between error geniusmoves that are not uniquely
defined and ones that are overdetermined.  For example, the first kind
happens when your source points and your destination points are collinear.
The second kind happens when you have collinear source points but
noncollinear destination points.

Are you going to worry about Geniusmoves that can be defined in special
cases by less data?  If so, sometimes the Geniusmove can be executed
before all of the data is put in, and sometimes an error can be determined
before all the data is put in.  It would be nice for the program to act
automatically as soon as it has enough information, but this requires some
fancy calculations of the dimension of the selected block.

In an Affinemove, if the first two lines have the same source but
different destination, it is already an error regardless of the third
line.

In an Affinemove, it is possible that collinear sources are OK as long as
the block is collinear and the destination points are also collinear and
the line containing the sources is the same as the line containing the
block.

In an Affinemove on a collinear block, two sources on the line containing
the block already determine the move.

Lots of interesting special cases arise with singleton blocks.  In an
Affinemove, one line determines the move as long as the source is the
selected point.  In an Affinemove, two lines determine the move as the
long as the selected point lies on the line connecting the sources.  In a
Rotationmove, you don't need the angle if the origin of the rotation is
the same as the selected point.  In a Shearmove, you don't need the line
if the origin of the shear is the same as the selected point.

Dan



