X-Status: A


NP is an undefined value on the last sheet.

DIR(P) = N, but it should be an undefined value.  DIRFROM(P P) does give
an error, and then defaults to N.

When you make lots of beats (like 1024 or 32768, for example), weird stuff
happens to the continuity.  I tried marching points off the field.  When I
went 16 steps, everything worked fine.  When I went further, some of the
points disappear from the screen until several beats after they should
have.  When I went very far, the points never disappeared; they just
stayed where they were the whole time.  When I tried EVEN REM NP with
32768 beats and NP on the field, the points moved the opposite direction!

Undoing Set Beats.... is screwed up.  Try changing the beats, then undoing
twice.  You'll see what's wrong.

----------------------------------------

Why haven't we ever allowed for point variables?  Reference points are
sort of like that, but they are a bit cumbersome sometimes.  It might be
worth developing a new aspect of the language for manipulating point
values.  For example, VECTOR(8 N) is a vector of length 8 heading N.  You
could use it in expressions like FMTO SP + VECTOR(8 N).  This seems useful
to me and not too hard to implement.  Note that vectors are not the same
datatype as points, so maybe it gets a bit complicated from a programmer's
point of view. 

There could also be ways to express absolute points on the field in the
form SPOT(45 EH).  This is the point on the east hash on the north 45 yard
line.  There would have to be a convention that the north endzone is the 0
yard line and the south endzone is the 100 yard line (or vice versa). 
We'd need new constants ES, EH, WH, WS for sidelines and hashes.  By
choosing a convention for positive east-west direction, you can express
more general points with expressions of the form ES+8.  Or even better,
with SPOT(45 EH) + VECTOR(8 E). 

Note that you can't add two points directly, but you can add one point to
arbitrarily many vectors.  You can also negate vectors (i.e., subtract a
vector from a point), and you can multiply vectors by numbers.  Of course,
you can't negate or multiply points.  Scalar multiplication takes care of
manipulating the length of vectors, and there should be some sort of
rotation function for changing the direction of vectors.

Both VECTOR and SPOT seem pretty handy to me.  Why haven't we ever talked
about this?  Or maybe we have, but I've forgotten.


