On Tue, 16 Dec 1997, Dan Isaksen wrote:

> Non-unique names won't cause any big problems, but some Stunt member is
> going to lose something valuable because his temporary file was
> overwritten by another copy of the program, so he couldn't recover after a
> crash. 

Well, the autosave file is local to a machine, so this would only happen
if you run it multiple times on the same machine (which would be the same
user under Windows).  Doing it correctly is a little harder.  If both
programs start at the same time, no autosave files exist yet, so how do
they pick different files?  I'll come up with something better.

> It is hard to test behavior after crashing because it is getting harder to
> make it crash these days.  

Glad to hear it.

> Clicking on a selected point should do blockmove on the selected block.
> Clicking on an unselected point when no other points are selected should
> select that single point and then do a blockmove on the singleton block.
> I think it is correct to think of individualmove as a special case of
> blockmove where the block is singleton.  Clicking on an unselected point
> when other points are selected should deselect the other points, select
> the clicked point, and blockmove that one point.  Shift-clicking on an
> unselected point when other points are selected should leave the other
> points selected, add the clicked point to the block, and blockmove the
> whole block.

I'd like to make shift get used as little as possible.  I think the idea
of making individual moves faster than block selections of individual
points is the correct one.  So the only change is for clicking on selected
points.

> We have AND blocking with shift.  We really should have XOR blocking, or
> at least a way to subtract points from a block without having to start
> from scratch.

I think I might have done this already, but I can't remember.  What might
be better is to have another mode (like the Blockmove mode) that only does
selections.  Clicking on a point toggles it between selected and
unselected.  You select a block of individual points by just clicking on
them.  If you start a lasso selection by clicking on a point, that point
will be toggled and all the points in that selection will match the
starting point (or maybe they should be toggled?)  I suppose you could
select different operations like AND, OR, XOR.

> I guess Scalemove would be OK.  I was thinking about the sound of these
> names this morning when walking to the university, and I came up with the
> following idea.  In order to sound right, a prefix for -move has to be one
> syllable (like Shearmove or Smartmove) or has to be more than one syllable
> with the accent not on the last syllable (like Affinemove and Geniusmove
> but not like Rescalemove).

Okay, Scalemove it is.

> I don't like Direction of Normal.  Even Direction of Noise would be
> better.  Direction of Face or Direction of Front unfortunately have the
> wrong abbreviation.
>  
> Should we put these two terminology questions to calchart-discussion?

Perhaps.  I'm not sure if anyone on there would be interested, but I'll
post a message (and try to get them to test it too... you're doing a great
jobs so far, but it would be good to get some feedback from someone
unfamiliar with the new version.)  Also, what about the terminology of
"point", "location", etc.  We've been using "point" loosely to mean a
bandsman or a location on the field.  Do we need a strict definition of
"point"?  I could ask on calchart-discussion also.

> I'm not sure I understand what Dilationmove is supposed to do.  Describe
> it to me so that I can see whether it makes sense or not.

It's not a general dilation, but only along the E-W N-S basic vectors.
I'm sure you'd probably like a more general version.  The interface works
like this.  Here's your block:

    Y
   +
**X
* *
C**

where C is the center, X is where you start the move, Y is where you end
it, and + is just a placeholder for illustration.  The block spacing will
be doubled:

* * Y

* X *

C * *

So you're moving a point to its new location to set the scale factor.  
Does this clear things up or would you like the formulas I used?

Gurk



