I wonder if EITHER would be more useful if it took three directions as
arguments, rather than two directions and a point.  The new EITHER could
function as the old EITHER in the following way

   EITHER(<direction1> <direction2> DIR(<point>))

There's a backwards compatibility problem, unless we allow both
possibilities and make the program smart enough to figure out which one to
consider based on the datatype of the third argument.  The new suggestion
is strictly more general than the old one; that's why I like it.


EITHER gives an error if the point argument is P, as it should.  When I
choose to ignore errors, the program makes an unpredictable choice of
default direction.  How is it doing this?


Did I already tell you that DIR(P) gives no error, but equals N?


If you use the command MT STEP(2 0 R1) E, you get a Ran out of time error.
STEP(x 0 p) should be undefined (or even better, it should equal
infinity).  I suspect that this is also a bug in version 2 because I don't
ever remember thinking about this before.

I still can't tell exactly what Dilationmove is supposed to do.  It seems
that N/S and E/W are preferred directions.  I don't like that.  There
should be an intuitive and coordinate-free way of handling this.  Send me
your code for calculating positions under Dilationmove.

Dan


