On Sat, 20 Dec 1997, Dan Isaksen wrote:

> When does a continuity edit become undoable?  Only after an animation?
> That doesn't seem frequent enough for me.  Certainly it is not necessary
> to undo every keystroke.  However, it makes some sense to allow for an
> undo as soon as some other action (other than keystrokes to the continuity
> editor) is done.

I forgot to answer this one.  Currently, it's limited for technical
reason.  The text window is pretty much independent.  Sometimes calchart
will compare the window to the actual continuity to see if it's changed,
and then it will be registered.  I think the only times are when the
window's closed, when the show is animated, when the show is saved, when
you quit, and when you change sheets.  The technical limitation may have
changed now, so I'll have to look into it.  I know, it's ugly.

Gurk



